{"title_page": "People's Protection Units", "text_new": "{{redirect|YPG}}\n{{distinguish|Women's Protection Units}}\n{{short description|Mainly-Kurdish militia in Syria}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = People's Protection Units\n| native_name = {{lang|ku|Yek\u00eeney\u00ean Parastina Gel (YPG)}} <br />{{rtl-lang|ar|{{rlm}}\u0648\u062d\u062f\u0627\u062a \u062d\u0645\u0627\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0628{{lrm}}{{lrm}}}}\n| image = People's Protection Units Flag.svg\n| caption = Flag of the YPG\n| dates = 2011\u2013present\n| allegiance = {{flagicon image|Flag of the Kurdish Supreme Committee.svg}} [[Kurdish Supreme Committee]] (2011\u20132013)<ref name=casualties/><br/>{{flag|Rojava}} (2013\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/13112013|title=PYD announces surprise interim government in Syria's Kurdish regions|publisher=[[Rudaw Media Network|Rudaw]]|accessdate=9 October 2014|date=13 November 2013}}</ref><br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag_of_the_Democratic_Union_Party.svg}} [[Democratic Union Party (Syria)|Democratic Union Party]] (2011\u2013present)\n| type = [[Light infantry]] militia with several [[Technical (vehicle)|motorised]] battalions\n| size = 35 000 {{small|(Including YPJ, 2017 estimate)}}{{sfnp|Rashid|2018|p=16}}\n| command_structure = {{flagicon image|Flag of Syrian Democratic Forces.svg}} [[Syrian Democratic Forces]]<!-- affects the field \"Part of\"-->\n| garrison_label = Garrison\n| motto = ''YPG dime\u015fe, erd \u00fb ezman diheje'' (YPG is marching, and the earth and sky [''or'' heavens] tremble)\n| march = \n| battles = [[Syrian Civil War]]\n* [[Rojava conflict#YPG claims territory|2012 Rojava campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Aleppo (2012\u2013present)|Battle of Aleppo]]\n** [[Northern Aleppo offensive (2016)]]\n* [[Al-Hasakah Governorate campaign (2012\u201313)]]\n** [[Battle of Ras al-Ayn]]\n** [[Battle of al-Yaarubiyah]]\n* [[Battle of Tell Abyad (2013)]]\n* [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]]\n* [[Al-Hasakah offensive (February\u2013March 2015)|Al-Hasakah offensive]]\n* [[Battle of Sarrin (June\u2013July 2015)|Battle of Sarrin]]\n* [[Tell Abyad offensive]]\n* [[Battle of Al-Hasakah (June\u2013August 2015)|Battle of Al-Hasakah]]\n* [[Al-Hawl offensive]]\n* [[Tishrin Dam offensive]]\n* [[Al-Shaddadi offensive (2016)|Al-Shaddadi offensive]]\n* [[Battle of Tell Abyad (2016)]]\n* [[Northern Raqqa offensive (May 2016)|Northern Raqqa offensive]]\n* [[Manbij offensive]]\n* [[Battle of al-Hasakah (2016)]]\n* [[Western al-Bab offensive (October\u2013November 2016)]]\n* [[Raqqa campaign (2016\u20132017)]]\n* [[Turkish military operation in Afrin]]\n* [[Eastern Syria Insurgency]]\n* [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria]]\n[[Iraqi Civil War (2014\u20132017)|Iraqi Civil War]]\n* [[December 2014 Sinjar offensive|2014 Sinjar offensive]]\n* [[November 2015 Sinjar offensive|2015 Sinjar offensive]]\n<!--Commanders-->| website = {{Official website|https://www.ypgrojava.org/}}\n| commander1 = S\u00eepan Hemo\n| commander1_label = General Commander\n| commander2 = Nuri Mahmoud\n| commander2_label = Spokesperson\n| notable_commanders = Ciwan \u00cebrah\u00eem\n<!-- Insignia -->| identification_symbol = \n| identification_symbol_label = Emblem\n| identification_symbol_2 = [[File:YPG Insignia.svg|150px]]\n| identification_symbol_2_label = Insignia\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Campaignbox Rojava Revolution}}\n[[File:Syrian civil war 01 11 2015.png|thumb|Military situation in the Syrian Civil War in November 2015]]\n[[File:Syrian civil war 01 11 2018.png|thumb|Military situation in January 2019]]\n\nThe '''People's Protection Units''' or '''People's Defense Units''' ({{lang-ku|\u06cc\u06d5\u06a9\u06cc\u0646\u06d5\u06a9\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u067e\u0627\u0631\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0646\u06cc \u06af\u06d5\u0644 |Yek\u00eeney\u00ean Parastina Gel}} ('''YPG''') {{IPA-ku|j\u025bki\u02d0n\u025bje\u02d0n p\u0251\u02d0\u027e\u0251\u02d0st\u026fn\u0251\u02d0 \u0261\u025bl|pron}}; {{lang-ar|\u0648\u062d\u062f\u0627\u062a \u062d\u0645\u0627\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0628|Wa\u1e25d\u0101t \u1e24im\u0101yat a\u0161-\u0160a\u02bdb}}; {{lang-syc|\u071a\u0715\u071d\u0308\u0718\u072c\u0710 \u0715\u0723\u0718\u072c\u072a\u0710 \u0715\u0725\u0721\u0710|translit=\u1e24doywotho d'Sutoro d'Amo}}) is a mainly-[[Kurds in Syria|Kurdish]] militia in Syria and the primary component of the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/ascent-of-the-pyd-and-the-sdf |title=Ascent of the PYD and the SDF |last1=Barfi |first1=Barak |date=April 2016 |publisher=Washington Institute for Near East Policy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2016/02/kurds-turkey-pkk-ypg/470991/|title=Who Exactly Are 'the Kurds'?|first=Steven A.|last=Cook|work=The Atlantic |accessdate=16 February 2017|date=25 February 2016}}</ref> The YPG mostly consists of ethnic [[Kurdish people|Kurds]], but also includes Arabs and [[Foreign fighters in the Syrian and Iraqi Civil Wars|foreign volunteers]]; it is closely allied to the [[Syriac Military Council]], a militia of [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]]. The YPG was formed in 2011 . It expanded rapidly in the [[Syrian Civil War]] and came to predominate over other armed Kurdish groups. A sister group, the [[Women's Protection Units]] (YPJ), fights alongside them. The YPG is active in [[Rojava|Northern and Eastern Syria]].\n\nIn early 2015, the group won a major victory over the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) during the [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]], where the YPG began to receive air and ground support from the United States and other [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve]] militaries. Since then, the YPG has primarily fought against ISIL, as well as on occasion fighting other [[Syrian opposition|Syrian rebel groups]] and the [[Turkish Armed Forces]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/kurdish-forces-bolster-assad-in-aleppo|title=Kurdish Forces Bolster Assad in Aleppo|publisher=Washington Institute|language=en|access-date=2017-03-17 |date=29 July 2016}}</ref> In late 2015, the YPG founded the SDF, as an umbrella group to better incorporate Arabs and [[Sectarianism and minorities in the Syrian Civil War|minorities]] into the war effort. In 2016\u20132017, the SDF's [[Raqqa campaign (2016\u20132017)|Raqqa campaign]] led to the liberation of the city of [[Raqqa]], the Islamic State's ''de facto'' capital. Several western sources have described the YPG as the \"most effective\" force in fighting ISIL in Syria.<ref>{{cite news|title=Turkey v Syria's Kurds v Islamic State|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-33690060|agency=BBC|date=23 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=US troops wearing YPG patches in Syria|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/us-soldiers-ypg-patches-syria-2016-5|work=Business Insider|date=27 May 2016}}</ref> A [[light infantry]] force, the YPG has limited military equipment and few [[armoured vehicles]].\n\n== History ==\n\n===2004: Early origins===\nKurdish youth attempted to unify themselves following the [[2004 Qamishli riots]]. The riots began as clashes between rivaling football fans before taking a political turn, with Arab fans raising pictures of [[Saddam Hussein]] while the Kurdish fans reportedly proclaimed \"We will sacrifice our lives for Bush\". This resulted in clashes between the two groups who attacked each other with sticks, stones and knives. Government security forces entered the city to quell the riot, firing at the crowds. The riots resulted in around 36 dead, most of them Kurds.\n\nThey did not, however, emerge as a significant force until the [[Syrian Civil War]] erupted in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=UA 15/05 Torture and ill-treatment/ possible unfair trial |url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/88000/mde240032005en.pdf |website=amnesty.org}}</ref><ref name=\"Vice\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/read/meet-the-ypg|title=Meet the YPG, the Kurdish militia that doesn't want help from anyone|last=Gold|first=Danny|date=31 October 2012|quote=A member of YPG\u2019s central command \u2026 said that the YPG formed in 2004 shortly after the Qamishlo riots, when a number of Kurdish youth realized that they needed to be able to defend themselves more efficiently. They did not officially declare themselves until the revolution started in 2011.|magazine=[[Vice (magazine)|VICE]]|accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011: Establishment ===\nExisting underground Kurdish political parties, namely the [[Democratic Union Party (Syria)|Democratic Union Party]] (PYD) and the [[Kurdish National Council]] (KNC), joined to form the [[Kurdish Supreme Committee]] (KSC) and established the People's Protection Units (YPG) militia to defend Kurdish-inhabited areas in northern Syria.<ref>{{cite web |last1=YPG |title=About Us |url=https://www.ypgrojava.org/About-Us |website=ypgrojava.org |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=casualties>{{cite news|title=Armed Kurds Surround Syrian Security Forces in Qamishli |url=http://www.rudaw.net/english/news/syria/4984.html |accessdate=27 July 2012 |publisher=Rudaw |date=22 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724224808/http://www.rudaw.net/english/news/syria/4984.html |archivedate=24 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===July 2012: Control of Kurdish areas===\nIn July 2012, the YPG had a standoff with Syrian government forces in the Kurdish city of [[Koban\u00ee]] and the surrounding areas. After negotiations, government forces withdrew and the YPG took control of [[Koban\u00ee]], [[Amuda]], and [[Afrin, Syria|Afrin]].<ref name=casualties/><ref>{{cite news|title=Kurds Give Ultimatum to Syrian Security Forces|url=http://www.ekurd.net/mismas/articles/misc2012/7/syriakurd541.htm |accessdate=9 October 2014|publisher=Rudaw|date=21 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nBy December 2012, it had expanded to 8 [[Brigade (military)|brigades]], which were formed in [[Qamishlo]], [[Koban\u00ee]], and [[Ras al-Ayn]] (Ser\u00ea Kaniy\u00ea) and in the districts of [[Afrin District|Afrin]], [[Al-Malikiyah District|al-Malikiyah]], and [[Al-Bab District|al-Bab]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://scientiahumana.org/2012/12/04/the-kurdish-protection-units-have-formed-a-new-brigade-in-the-al-bab-region |title=The Kurdish Protection Units have formed a new brigade in the Al\u2013Bab region |work=Scientia Humana |date=4 December 2012 |accessdate=18 December 2013 |quote=Kurdish Information Center |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108025429/http://scientiahumana.org/2012/12/04/the-kurdish-protection-units-have-formed-a-new-brigade-in-the-al-bab-region |archivedate=8 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Late 2012: Islamist attacks make YPG dominant===\nThe YPG did not initially take an offensive posture in the Syrian Civil War. Aiming mostly to defend Kurdish-majority areas, it avoided engaging Syrian government forces, which still controlled several enclaves in Kurdish territory. The YPG changed this policy when Ras al-Ayn was taken by the [[al-Qaeda]]-affiliated [[al-Nusra Front]]. At first the YPG conquered the surrounding government-controlled areas: [[al-Darbasiyah]] (Kurdish: Dirb\u00eas\u00ee), [[Tel Tamer]] and [[al-Malikiyah]] (Kurdish: D\u00earika Hemko) in order to prevent the FSA from gaining more power in the area.{{Citation needed|date=March 2016}} The subsequent [[Battle of Ras al-Ayn]] started in earnest when on 19 November 2012, the al-Nusra Front and a second al-Qaeda affiliate, [[Ghuraba al-Sham]], attacked Kurdish positions in the town. The battle ended with a YPG victory in July 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/2/8/76750/World/Region/Kurds-expel-jihadists-from-flashpoint-Syrian-town-.aspx |title=Kurds expel jihadists from flashpoint Syrian town: NGO|agency=AFP|work=Al-Ahram Weekly|date=17 July 2013|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhile many rebel groups clashed with the YPG, [[jihadist]] and [[Salafist]] groups did so the most often.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |author=International Crisis Group |title=Flight of Icarus? The PYD\u2019s Precarious Rise in Syria |date=8 May 2014 |quote=While rebel groups from across the ideological spectrum have clashed with the PYD, jihadi and Salafi groups have done so most aggressively and consistently |accessdate=20 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220181554/http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |archive-date=20 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The YPG proved to be the only Kurdish militia able to effectively resist the fundamentalists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rudaw.net/english/interview/22072013 |title=YPG Commander: Kurds Are Bulwark Against Islamic Extremism in Syria|publisher=Rudaw|accessdate=9 October 2014|date=22 July 2013}}</ref> While the YPG protected the Kurdish communities it was able to extract a price: it prevented the emergence of new, rival militias and forced existing ones to cooperate with or join the YPG forces on its terms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |author=International Crisis Group |title=Flight of Icarus? The PYD\u2019s Precarious Rise in Syria |date=8 May 2014 |quote=The PYD\u2019s growing influence largely has come at the expense of other Kurdishgroups. In particular, it has prevented emergence of new, rival militias while forcing existing ones to cooperate with or join PYD forces on their terms |accessdate=20 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220181554/http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |archive-date=20 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This was how the Islamist attacks enabled the YPG to unite the Syrian Kurds under its banner<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf|author=International Crisis Group|title=Flight of Icarus? The PYD\u2019s Precarious Rise in Syria|date=8 May 2014|quote=Crisis Group interview, Erbil, 4 July 2013: Intensified Islamist attacks in Kurdish areas shifted Kurdish public opinion toward the PYD. A resident of Tell Tamr, a partly Kurdish town targeted by armed Islamist groups, said, \"in the aftermath of the battle of Ras al-Ayn, Islamists entered Tell Tamr. They began kidnapping and killing Kurds. I am not a YPG supporter, and I will never be. But if it weren\u2019t for the YPG, not a single Kurd would be left in the [al-] Jazeera region\". Crisis Group interview, Erbil, July 2013. A journalist working for a pro-KDP channel commented: \"I was the most critical person against the PYD. But at the moment, I have to admit that they are saving the people from the worst\".|accessdate=20 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220181554/http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf|archive-date=20 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and caused<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |author=International Crisis Group |title=Flight of Icarus? The PYD\u2019s Precarious Rise in Syria |date=8 May 2014 |quote=\"At the same time, Ankara turned a blind eye to the Islamist fighters crossing from Turkey into Syria, viewing them \u2013 in addition to helping bring down the Assad regime \u2013 as potential counterweights to the PYD. The strategy backfired; the PYD not only gained territory, but also bolstered its appeal among Kurds as their only protector from jihadis. In September 2013, a Turkish official acknowledged: 'We made the PYD stronger by trying to undermine it'\" |accessdate=20 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220181554/http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |archive-date=20 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> it to become the de facto army of the Syrian Kurds.<ref name=\"bb\">{{cite book|last1=N. Abboud|first1=Samer|title=Syria|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-7456-9801-4|page=116|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BPbrCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT116}}</ref><ref name=\"nn\">{{cite news|title=Kurdish Woman Leading Battle Against Islamic State in Kobane: Activists|url=http://www.ndtv.com/world-news/kurdish-woman-leading-battle-against-islamic-state-in-kobane-activists-678354|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"aus\">{{cite news|title=Woman leads Kurds in battle against Islamic State in Kobane: activists|url=http://www.smh.com.au/world/woman-leads-kurds-in-battle-against-islamic-state-in-kobane-activists-20141013-1158kr.html|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"enalb\">{{cite news|title=Kurdish woman leads fight against ISIS in Kobane|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/2014/10/14/Kurdish-woman-leads-fight-against-ISIS-in-Kobane-.html|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2013: Kurdish control of al-Yaarubiyah/Til Ko\u00e7er===\n{{main|Battle of al-Yaarubiyah}}\nIn October 2013, YPG fighters took control of [[al-Yaarubiyah]] (Til Ko\u00e7er) following intense clashes with ISIL. The clashes lasted about three days, with the Til Ko\u00e7er border gate to Iraq being taken in a major offensive launched on the night of 24 October.<ref name=\"til\" /> PYD leader Saleh Muslim told St\u00eark TV that this success created an alternative against efforts to hold the territory under embargo,<ref name=\"til\">{{cite news|url=http://en.firatajans.com/news/news/ypg-takes-control-of-til-kocer.htm |title=YPG takes control of Til Ko\u00e7er |date=27 October 2013 |agency=[[Firat News Agency]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209152741/http://en.firatajans.com/news/news/ypg-takes-control-of-til-kocer.htm |archivedate=9 December 2013}}</ref> referring to the fact that the other border crossings with Iraq led to areas controlled by the [[Kurdistan Regional Government]], while al-Yaarubiyah led to areas controlled by the Iraqi central government.\n\n===2014: Fight against ISIL===\n[[File:Rojava february 2014.png|250px|thumb|YPG-controlled territory, February 2014]]\nIn 2014, the [[Syriac Military Council]], a group of [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] units, was formally integrated into the YPG's command structure.\n\nThe [[inter-rebel conflict during the Syrian Civil War]] led to open war between the [[Free Syrian Army]] and ISIL in January 2014. The YPG collaborated with FSA groups to fight ISIL in [[Raqqa Governorate|Raqqa]] province;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aranews.net/2014/05/fsa-and-ypg-cooperate-against-isil-militants-in-syrias-tel-abyad/|title=FSA and YPG cooperate against ISIL militants in Syria's Tel Abyad|date=12 May 2014|publisher=ARA News|accessdate=9 October 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008154840/http://aranews.net/2014/05/fsa-and-ypg-cooperate-against-isil-militants-in-syrias-tel-abyad/|archivedate=8 October 2014}}</ref> the group also formed an operations room with multiple FSA factions, called [[Euphrates Volcano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aranews.net/2014/09/ypg-fsa-form-joint-military-chamber-combat-isis-syria/|title=YPG and FSA form a joint military chamber to combat ISIS in Syria|publisher=ARA News|date=12 September 2014|accessdate=9 October 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014063318/http://aranews.net/2014/09/ypg-fsa-form-joint-military-chamber-combat-isis-syria/|archivedate=14 October 2014}}</ref> However, the general outcome of this campaign was a massive advance by ISIL, which effectively separated the eastern part of Rojava from the main force of FSA rebels. ISIL followed up on its success by attacking the YPG and the FSA in Koban\u00ee Canton in March and fighting its way to the gates of the city of Koban\u00ee in September.\nThe actual [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]] approximately coincided with an escalation in the [[American-led intervention in Syria]]. This intervention had started with aiding the FSA against the government, but when the FSA was getting defeated by ISIL in eastern Syria, it escalated to bombing ISIL on Syrian territory.\n\nWith the world fearing another massacre in Koban\u00ee, American support increased substantially. The US gave intense [[close air support]] to the YPG, and in doing so, started military cooperation with one of the factions. While it expected that ISIL would quickly crush the YPG and the FSA, this alliance was not considered a problem for the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/10/08/world/meast/isis-threat/index.html |title=U.S. military: Airstrikes against ISIS won't save key city of Kobani|date=9 October 2014|publisher=CNN |accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref> The YPG won the battle in early 2015.\n\nMeanwhile, the situation had been stable in Afrin and Aleppo. The fight between the FSA and ISIL had led to a normalization in the relations between FSA and YPG since the end of 2013. In February 2015, the YPG signed a judicial agreement with the [[Levant Front]] in [[Aleppo Governorate|Aleppo]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=KURDISH YPG AND JABHAT AL-SHAMIYA AGREEMENT ON JUDICIARY COOPERATION IN ALEPPO|url=https://www.facebook.com/SyrianRebellionObservatory/photos/a.1648239072069399.1073741828.1648217982071508/1699722200254419/?type=1 |date=5 February 2015|publisher=Syrian Rebellion Observatory}}</ref><!--allys-->\n\n===Spring 2015: Offensive operations with coalition support===\n[[File:Rojava june 2015.png|250px|thumb|YPG-controlled territory, June 2015]]\nIn the spring 2015, [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] was close to capturing the Iraqi city of [[Battle of Ramadi (2014\u201315)|Ramadi]].{{Relevance inline|date=March 2017}} The YPG was able and willing to offensively engage and put pressure on ISIL and had built up a track record as a reliable military partner of the US. With American close air support, offensives near [[Eastern al-Hasakah offensive|Hasakah]] and from Hasakah [[Western al-Hasakah offensive|westward]] culminated in the [[Tell Abyad offensive|conquest of Tell Abyad]], linking up Koban\u00ee with Hasakah in July 2015.\n\nWith these offensives, the YPG had begun to make advances into areas that did not always have a Kurdish majority. When the YPG and the FSA entered the border town of [[Tell Abyad]] in June 2015, parts of the population fled the intense fighting and the airstrikes.<ref name=\"pitarakis\">{{cite news|last1=Pitarakis|first1=Lefteris|last2=Mroue|first2=Bassem|date=14 June 2015|title=Thousands of Syrians flee into Turkey amid intense fighting|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/7f62663318e94589bf6097825914a088/kurds-nearing-key-islamic-state-held-syrian-border-town |agency=AP|quote=Thousands of Syrians cut through a border fence and crossed over into Turkey \u2026 fleeing intense fighting \u2026 between Kurdish fighters and jihadis.}}</ref>\n\n===Autumn 2015: foundation of the SDF===\nThe [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] was established in Hasakah on 11 October 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/10/17/turkey-claim-syrian-kurds-terrorists-not-isis-ypg-pkk-sdf/|title=Why Is Turkey Fighting Syria's Kurds?|last=Abadi|first=Cameron|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref><ref name=\"KQ1015\">{{cite web|url=http://kurdishquestion.com/index.php/kurdistan/west-kurdistan/declaration-of-establishment-by-democratic-syria-forces/1179-declaration-of-establishment-by-democratic-syria-forces.html|title=Declaration of establishment by Syrian Democratic Forces|date=15 October 2015|publisher=Kurdish Question|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224085811/http://kurdishquestion.com/index.php/kurdistan/west-kurdistan/declaration-of-establishment-by-democratic-syria-forces/1179-declaration-of-establishment-by-democratic-syria-forces.html|archive-date=24 February 2016|accessdate=15 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It has its origins in the YPG-FSA collaboration against ISIL, which had previously led to the establishment of the [[Euphrates Volcano|Euphrates Volcano joint operations room]] in 2014. Many of the partners are the same, and even the logo / flag with the Blue Euphrates symbol has common traits with that of Euphrates Volcano. The primary difference is that Euphrates Volcano was limited to coordinating the activities of independent Kurdish and Arab groups, while the SDF is a single organisation made up of Kurds, Arabs, and [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]].\n\nThe first success of the SDF was the capture of the strategic ethnically Arab town of al-Hawl from ISIL during the [[2015 Al-Hawl offensive|al-Hawl offensive]] in November 2015. This was followed in December by the [[Tishrin Dam offensive]]. The dam was captured on 26 December. Participating forces included the YPG, the FSA group [[Army of Revolutionaries]], the tribal group [[al-Sanadid Forces]] and the Assyrian [[Syriac Military Council]]. The coalition had some heavy weapons and was supported by intense US led airstrikes.<ref name=\"reuters-alliance\">{{cite news |date=28 December 2015 |title=U.S.-backed alliance captures key dam from Islamic State \u2013 alliance spokesman |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-mideast-crisis-syria-alliance-idUKKBN0U90DC20151228 |agency=[[Reuters]] |quote=Colonel Talal Selo ... said the rapid advance overnight by thousands of troops from the Democratic Forces of Syria had brought the dam ... under their control on Saturday.... Selo said ... the latest round of fighting ... involved several thousand fighters from the Democratic Forces of Syria with heavy armour. }}</ref> The capture of the hydroelectric dam also had positive effects on the [[economy of Rojava]].<ref name=\"Themedialine\">{{cite news |date=1 February 2016 |title= Photos of Tishrin Dam, Liberated from ISIS |url=http://www.themedialine.org/views/blog/photos-of-tishrin-dam-liberated-from-isis/ |quote=Tishrin is an incredible dam, not least of all because of the fact that it sits cradled in a beautiful lush valley, in an otherwise dry and arid land. But also because of what Tishrin implies for the people of Rojava who have survived for the past two years under incredible economic and political conditions, exacerbated significantly by lack of access to water and electricity which Tishrin provides.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Claimed and de facto territory of Rojava.png|thumb|210px|SDF-controlled territory (green), claimed territory (orange), [[Turkish occupation of northern Syria|Turkish-occupied Afrin]] (red) in October 2018]]\n\n===2016===\nIn February, the YPG-led SDF launched the [[Al-Shaddadi offensive (2016)|al-Shaddadi offensive]], followed by the [[Manbij offensive]] in May, and [[Raqqa offensive (2016\u2013present)|the Raqqa]] and [[Aleppo offensive (November\u2013December 2016)|Aleppo offensives]] in November. These operations extended SDF-controlled territory, usually at ISIL's expense.\n\nOn 7 April 2016, the Kurdish neighborhood of [[Sheikh Maqsood]] in Aleppo was shelled with [[Mortar (weapon)|mortars]] that may have contained [[List of chemical warfare agents|chemical agents]] (160 killed or wounded).<ref>{{cite web|title=MAPPING MILITANT ORGANIZATIONS: Jaish al-Islam|url=https://web.stanford.edu/group/mappingmilitants/cgi-bin/groups/view/533|website=Stanford University|date=31 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.com/en/concerns-grow-about-abuses-war-crimes-in-syria/a-19277777 |title= Middle East Concerns grow about abuses, war crimes in Syria |work=Deutsche Welle|date=25 May 2016}}</ref> Spokesperson for the YPG said that [[Saudi Arabia]]-backed [[Jaysh al-Islam]] (Army of Islam) rebel group has attacked the Kurdish neighborhood of Aleppo with \"forbidden weapons\" many times since the war's start.<ref>\"[http://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/7a0f6294-ab7f-4d15-b5af-3ff4b444ab3f/Syrian-rebels-admit-chemical-use-against-Kurds Syrian rebels admit chemical use against Kurds]\". [[Kurdistan 24]]. 9 April 2016.</ref>\n\n===2018: Turkish military intervention===\n{{See also|Turkish military intervention in Syria (January 2018\u2013present)}}\n\n== Women's Protection Units ==\n{{main|Women's Protection Units}}\n[[File:YPJ fighters shake hands with one another.jpg|thumb|Women's Protection Units in November 2014]]\nThe [[Women's Protection Units]] (YPJ), also known as the Women's Defense Units, is the YPG's female brigade, which was set up in 2012. Kurdish media have said that YPJ troops became vital during the [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Trieb|first1=Erin|title=Meet the Kurdish Women Fighting ISIS in Syria|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/isis-terror/meet-kurdish-women-fighting-isis-syria-n199821|accessdate=19 March 2016|agency=NBC News|date=August 2014}}</ref> Consisting of approximately 20,000 fighters, they make up around 40% of the YPG.<ref name=\"profil\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/profil-rojda-felat-1.3239571|title=Profil - Rojda Felat. Kommandeurin der Offensive gegen den IS in Raqqa und Bismarck-Fan. [Profile - Rojda Felat. Commander of the offensive against the IS in Raqqa and Bismarck-Fan]|publisher=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]]|language=German|author=Moritz Baumstieger|date=9 November 2016|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref> {{Dubious|date=August 2019}}\n\n== Organization ==\n\n=== Flags ===\n{{multiple image\n | align = center\n | total_width = 600\n | header = Flags of the People's Protection Units\n \n | image1 = People's Protection Units Flag (2011-2012, Vertical).svg\n | caption1 = Vertical red flag of the YPG, used since 2011 until early 2013\n\n | image2 = People's Protection Units Flag (2011-2012).svg\n | caption2 = Horizontal red flag of the YPG, used since 2011 until early 2013\n\n | image3 = People's Protection Units Flag (2011-2012) alternative.svg\n | caption3 = Variant of the horizontal red flag, also used until early 2013\n\n | image4 = People's Protection Units Flag.svg\n | caption4 = Yellow flag of the YPG, first used since late 2012, widely adopted in 2013 and since then the official flag of the militia\n}}\n\n=== Units ===\nIn 2017, the YPG began to form units called [[regiment]]s in translation, though they are smaller than comparable units in standard militaries:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Canton\n! style=\"width:5%;\"| Number\n! style=\"width:40%;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Date Established\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Strength\n|-\n| Afrin  || 1 || Martyr Xebat D\u00earik  || 27 Feb 2017 || 236 in 4 battalions\n|-\n| Afrin  || 2 || Martyr Afrin  || 20 April 2017 || 235\n|-\n| Afrin  || 3 || Martyr Rojhilet  || Early June? 2017 || 236\n|-\n| Afrin  || 4 || Martyr Mazloum  || 2 July 2017 || 234\n|-\n| Afrin  || 5 || Martyr Ali\u015f\u00ear  || 27 August 2017 || 303\n|-\n| Afrin  || 7 || Martyr Jayan  || 23 Oct 2017 || 250\n|-\n| Afrin  || 8 || Martyr Bahoz Afrin  || 18 Nov 2017 || 234\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Canton\n! style=\"width:5%;\"| Number\n! style=\"width:40%;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Date Established\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Strength\n|-\n| Kobane || 1 || ?  || 13 Feb 2017 || 80\n|-\n| Kobane  || 2 || Martyr \u015eevger Koban\u00ee Regiment || 18 Feb 2017 || 90\n|-\n| Jazira - al-Hasakah || 1 || Jian Judy and Dogan Fadel  || 20 July 2017 || 500\n|-\n| Jazira - Girk\u00ea Leg\u00ea || 3 || Qere\u00e7ox Martyrs  || 12 July 2017 || 200\n|-\n| Aleppo || 1 || Martyr Shahid Baqour || 30 Sep 2017 || 55 (Martyr Abu Shayar battalion)\n|-\n| Tabqa (SDF) || 1 || Martyr Haboun Arab || 14 Nov 2017 || 250\n|}\n\n=== Tactics ===\nAccording to a report in [[IHS Jane's]] regarding the YPG,\n\n{{quote|Relying on speed, stealth, and surprise, it is the archetypal guerrilla army, able to deploy quickly to front lines and concentrate its forces before quickly redirecting the axis of its attack to outflank and ambush its enemy. The key to its success is autonomy. Although operating under an overarching tactical rubric, YPG brigades are inculcated with a high degree of freedom and can adapt to the changing battlefield.<ref name=\"YPG strategy\">{{cite news |title=Analysis: YPG \u2013 the Islamic State's worst enemy |url=http://www.janes.com/article/43030/analysis-ypg-the-islamic-state-s-worst-enemy}}</ref>}}\n\nThe YPG relies heavily on [[sniper]]s and backs them by suppressing enemy fire using mobile heavy machine guns. It also uses roadside bombs to prevent outflanking maneuvers, particularly at night. Its lines have generally held when attacked by [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) forces who have better equipment, including helmets and body armor.<ref name=\"stephens\">{{cite news| title=Analysis: YPG \u2013 The Islamic State's worst enemy |url=http://www.janes.com/article/43030/analysis-ypg-the-islamic-state-s-worst-enemy |date=11 September 2014|accessdate=13 March 2016 |last=Stephens |first=Michael |newspaper=IHS Jane's 360 }}</ref>\n\nThe YPG and [[People's Defence Forces|People's Defense Forces]] (HPG) have also trained and equipped more than 1,000 [[Yazidis]], who operate in the [[Sinjar Mountains|Mount Sinjar area]] as local defense units under their supervision.<ref name=\"stephens\" />\n\nThe YPG calls itself a people's army, and therefore appoints officers by internal elections.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ahmad|first=Rozh|title=A rare glimpse into Kurdish armed forces in Syrian Kurdistan|work=[[Ekurd.net]]|location=Erbil, Iraq|date=6 August 2012|url=http://www.ekurd.net/mismas/articles/misc2012/8/syriakurd578.htm }}</ref>\n\nA 20-year-old female YPJ fighter named Zlukh Hamo (Nom de guerre: Avesta Khabur) was reported to have carried out a [[suicide attack]] towards Turkish troops and a tank during the early phase of the [[Turkish military operation in Afrin|Afrin Offensive]], killing herself and several soldiers in the process.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/28/world/middleeast/kurds-female-suicide-bomber-syria.html|title=Female Kurdish Fighter Kills Turkish Troops in Likely Suicide Bombing in Syria}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1235721/middle-east|title=Turkish troops targeted in Afrin suicide attack}}</ref> The attack was commended by pro-SDF sources as a courageous attack against a tank using explosives, which killed her in the process.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/280120182|title=Kurdish female fighter detonates herself to destroy a Turkish tank in Afrin, statement}}</ref>\n\n=== Equipment ===\n{{see also|List of military equipment used by Syrian Democratic Forces}}\nCompared to other factions engaged in the Syrian Civil war, the YPG has not received significant foreign assistance in the form of weapons and military equipment. According to the YPG, circumstances led to their capture of less equipment from the Syrian Army than other opposition groups did. The figures are estimates only based on the balance sheet that the YPG regularly publishes of its activities.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018Balance of the War Against Hostile Groups in Rojava, Northern Syria: Year 2015\u2019 |url=http://ypgrojava.com/en/2016/01/01/balance-of-the-war-against-hostile-groups-in-rojava-northern-syria-year-2015/ |accessdate=23 March 2016 |date=23 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126073438/http://ypgrojava.com/en/2016/01/01/balance-of-the-war-against-hostile-groups-in-rojava-northern-syria-year-2015/ |archivedate=26 January 2016 }}</ref>\n\n== International outreach ==\n\n=== Foreign volunteers ===\n{{further|YPG International|International Freedom Battalion}}\n[[File:German, French, and Spanish YPG fighters.png|250px|left|thumb|[[Germans|German]], [[French people|French]], and [[Spanish people|Spanish]] fighters of the YPG in northern Syria.]]\nEx\u2013[[U.S. Army]] soldier [[Jordan Matson]] was among the first foreign volunteers of the YPG. Injured by an ISIL suicide bomb, he developed the \"Lions of Rojava\" recruitment campaign for foreign volunteers,<ref>{{cite web |author=Jennifer Percy |title=Meet the American Vigilantes Who Are Fighting ISIS |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/04/magazine/meet-the-american-vigilantes-who-are-fighting-isis.html |date=30 September 2015 |accessdate=15 December 2015}}</ref> launched on 21 October 2014 on Facebook.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/The-Lions-Of-Rojava/290140627860127|title=The Lions of Rojava|accessdate=15 November 2014|publisher=Facebook}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/islamic-state-ypg-foreign-fighters/26690432.html|title=Kobani Kurds Use Facebook To Recruit Foreign Fighters in Struggle Against IS |date=13 November 2014|accessdate=15 November 2014|publisher=Radio Free Europe Radio Liberty}}</ref> More than 400 volunteers from Europe, the Americas and Australia have joined the YPG {{As of|2015|6|11|lc=y}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/2015/06/more-than-400-fighters-from-australia-america-and-europe-join-ypg|title=SOHR|date=11 June 2015|accessdate=15 November 2015|publisher=Syriahr.com}}</ref> including at least ten U.S. volunteers, three of which were U.S. Army veterans.<ref name=Shah>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/culture/western-comrades-join-kurds-arabs-secularists-yezidis-and-syriac-christians-against-islamic-state_27563|title=Western \"comrades\" join Kurds, Arabs, secularists, Yezidis, and Syriac Christians against Islamic State|date=29 October 2014|accessdate=13 February 2015|publisher=Your Middle East}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/10/06/jordan-matson-joins-kurds-against-islamic-state/16796487/|title=Exclusive: American explains why he's fighting ISIL|date=7 October 2014|accessdate=23 October 2014|publisher=USA Today}}</ref><ref name=bbc23oct>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-29705167|title=The US volunteers who fight with Syria's Kurds|date=23 October 2014|accessdate=23 October 2014|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/article/a-divorced-father-of-two-from-ohio-is-fighting-the-islamic-state-in-syria|title=A Divorced Father-of-Two from Ohio Is Fighting the Islamic State in Syria|date=23 October 2014|accessdate=13 February 2015|publisher=Vice News}}</ref> People from both China and the Chinese diaspora have also joined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-35036879|title=The Chinese man fighting Islamic State with the YPG|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOther prominent foreign volunteers have included [[Brace Belden]], [[Macer Gifford]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/islamic-state/11668576/British-ex-trader-who-fought-Isil-describes-escape-from-Syria.html|title=British ex-trader who fought Isil describes escape from Syria|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en}}</ref> Ryan Lock,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jan/02/briton-ryan-lock-killed-while-fighting-against-isis-in-syria|title=Briton killed while fighting against Isis in Syria|last=Blake|first=Matt|date=2017-01-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Michael Israel,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2016/12/3/foreign-volunteers-fighting-with-syrian-kurdish-forces-killed-by-turkey|title=Foreign volunteers fighting with Syrian-Kurdish forces killed 'by Turkey'|last=Arab|first=The New|work=alaraby|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en}}</ref> Dean Evans,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/oct/29/isis-wasnt-about-killing-people-what-drove-british-farmer-syrian-frontline|title='It wasn't about killing people': what drove a British farmer to the Syrian frontline?|last=Blake|first=Matt|date=2016-10-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[Jac Holmes]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rudaw.net/english/kurdistan/240420166|title=Three foreign YPG volunteers released from jail, going home |website=rudaw|access-date=2017-03-24}}</ref> [[Anna Campbell]], [[Lorenzo Orsetti]] and [[Haukur Hilmarsson]]. \n\nDozens of non-Kurdish Turks (from both Turkey and the European diaspora) have also joined.<ref name=Shah/> The Turkish [[Marxist-Leninist Communist Party (Turkey)|Marxist-Leninist Communist Party]] (MLKP) has been sending volunteers to fight in the YPG since 2012. At least four have been killed in battle as of February 2015\u2014one during the Battle of Ras al-Ayn and three during the Siege of Koban\u00ee. The party released a video in late January 2015 showing several Spanish- and German-speaking volunteers from Europe among its ranks in [[Jazira Canton]]; they were reorganised into the [[International Freedom Battalion]] on 10 June 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.etha.com.tr/Haber/2015/01/28/guncel/enternasyonal-devrimciler-her-dilden-devrimi-savun/|title=Enternasyonal devrimciler: Her dilden devrimi savunuyoruz|date=28 January 2015|publisher=Etkin Haber Ajans\u0131|language=Turkish|accessdate=11 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302131855/http://www.etha.com.tr/Haber/2015/01/28/guncel/enternasyonal-devrimciler-her-dilden-devrimi-savun/|archive-date=2 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===== Deaths =====\n{{Further information|International_Freedom_Battalion#International_Freedom_Battalion_fatalities}}\nDuring the fight against ISIL and the defense of [[Afrin, Syria|Afrin]] against the Turkish state, several of the international volunteers were wounded and killed. The [[Icelanders|Icelandic]] [[Haukur Hilmarsson]], aged 31, was killed on 24 February 2018 in an [[artillery]] attack by the [[Turkish army]] in the village of [[Maabatli|Mabeta]], Afrin.<ref>https://anfenglish.com/news/internationalists-martyred-in-rojava-remembered-in-greece-33183</ref> As a [[YPJ]] fighter, the British woman [[Anna Campbell]], 26, from [[Lewes]] in [[East Sussex]], was killed in a Turkish airstrike in [[Afrin, Syria|Afrin]] on 15 March 2018.<ref>https://www.rt.com/uk/421667-syria-afrin-ypg-campbell/</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/19/briton-kurds-anna-campbell-dies-fighting-turkey-syria-afrin</ref> In the battle of [[Al-Baghuz Fawqani]], an Italian man fighting for the YPG, [[Lorenzo Orsetti]], was killed on Sunday, 17 March 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-47628209|title=Syrian fighters 'overrun IS encampment'|date=2019-03-19|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\n===== Politics =====\n\nWhile most countries do not object in principle to their citizens joining the ranks of the YPG, Turkey has been vocal against YPG's foreign recruits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/en/originals/2017/06/turkey-syria-kurds-ypg-foreign-militants.html|title=Turkey increasingly vocal against YPG\u2019s foreign recruits|publisher=Al-Monitor|author=Metin Gurcan|date=28 June 2017|access-date=28 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929000711/http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/en/originals/2017/06/turkey-syria-kurds-ypg-foreign-militants.html|archive-date=29 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSeveral Australians, including former [[Australian labour movement|trade unionist]] and politician [[Matthew Gardiner]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/news/northern-territory/matthew-gardiner-confirmed-to-be-fighting-islamic-state-with-kurds/story-fnk0b1zt-1227203073161|title=Matthew Gardiner confirmed to be fighting Islamic State with Kurds|work=NTNews|accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref> have been involved with the YPG despite threats by Australia to prosecute any citizens involved in the Syrian Civil War.<ref name=\"xinhua\">{{cite news |date=11 June 2015 |title=Australian man defends his actions fighting against Islamic State |url=http://english.sina.com/2015/0610/818826.html |agency=[[Xinhua News Agency|Xinhua (Beijing)]] |quote=Former international junior bench press champion Ashley Dyball \u2026 wrote on Facebook, 'The s--- you see here is nothing like you see on the bias news reports, the Islamic state must be stopped and if it means I can\u2019t come home f--- it.' \u2026 Dyball faces prosecution if he returns.}}</ref> Under Australian law it is a criminal offence to fight with any side in a foreign conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lowyinterpreter.org/post/2015/03/25/Awkward-contradictions-in-Australian-foreign-fighter-laws.aspx|title=Awkward contradictions in Australian foreign-fighter laws|author=Lauren Williams|work=lowyinterpreter.org|accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Turkish court sentenced two [[Czech Republic|Czech]] nationals to more than six years in prison for their reported ties to the YPG.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkish Supreme Court upholds six-year verdict imposed on two Czechs |url=https://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/turkish-supreme-court-upholds-six-year-verdict-imposed-on-two-czechs |work=Radio Praha |date=24 July 2018}}</ref> In [[Germany]], the YPG leads to controversies as it is up to the police to begin a prosecution for showing a YPG flag.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peter|first=Erik|url=https://taz.de/!5629632/|title=Kurdische Symbole in Deutschland: Rechtslage? Mal so, mal so|date=2019-10-16|work=Die Tageszeitung: taz|access-date=2020-03-01|language=de|issn=0931-9085}}</ref> In the state of Bavaria, fines for showing a YPG flag are issued, while the federal government declares that the YPG is not forbidden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://anfdeutsch.com/aktuelles/ist-das-zeigen-einer-ypg-fahne-strafbar-7797|title=Ist das Zeigen einer YPG-Fahne strafbar?|website=ANF News|language=de|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>  \n\n=== Foreign government support ===\n{{See also|Syrian Democratic Forces}}\n\nBecause the YPG operates in a landlocked territory, rival opposition groups as well as the Turkish and Syrian government were able to physically prevent foreign aid from reaching it. The YPG's seizure of Til Ko\u00e7er in October 2013 (cf. above) created an overland connection to more or less friendly groups in Iraq, but could not change the even more fundamental problem, that the YPG had no allies willing to provide equipment.\n\n==== United States ====\n[[File:US and YPG officers in northeastern Hasaka.png|thumb|A US military officer and YPG and YPJ commanders tour an area hit by [[April 2017 Turkish airstrikes in Syria and Iraq|Turkish airstrikes]] in April 2017]]\n[[File:YPG and US army Hassaka 1-5-2017.jpg|thumb|U.S. Army [[M1126 Infantry Carrier Vehicle|M1126 Stryker]] armored vehicle in [[Al-Hasakah]], May 2017]]\nIn August 2014 [[Mazlum Kobane|Mazlum Koban\u00ee]] led negotiations with the US in [[Sulaymaniyah|Sulaymaniya]], which led to a military alliance against ISIL.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/dispatch/how-trump-betrayed-the-general-who-defeated-isis|title=How Trump Betrayed the General Who Defeated ISIS|last=Wright|first=Robin|date=2019-04-04|access-date=2019-04-05|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> The United States provided the YPG with air support during the [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-29526783|title=Kobane: Air strikes help Syria town curb IS|date=8 October 2014|accessdate=14 December 2016|via=bbc.com}}</ref> and during later campaigns, helping the YPG defend territory against attacks by the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/dec/01/syria-airstrikes-everything-you-need-to-know|title=Syria airstrikes: everything you need to know|first1=Matthew|last1=Weaver|first2=Julian|last2=Borger|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=14 December 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref> Turkey has criticised US support.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-35541003|title=Turkey's Erdogan denounces US support for Syrian Kurds|date=10 February 2016|accessdate=14 December 2016|via=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe YPG also received 27 bundles totalling 24 tons of small arms and ammunition and 10 tons of medical supplies from the United States and Iraqi Kurdistan during the Siege of Koban\u00ee.<ref name=\"pukmedia\">{{cite web|url=http://pukmedia.com/KS_Direje.aspx?Jimare=69493|title=PUKmedia \u06cc\u06d5\u06a9\u06ce\u062a\u06cc\u06cc \u0646\u06cc\u0634\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u06cc \u06a9\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646|work=pukmedia.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 October 2015, the US began an operation to airdrop 120 tons of military supplies to the YPG and its local Arab and Turkmen allies to fight ISIL north of [[Raqqa]]. The first airdrop consisted of 112 pallets of ammunition and 'other items like hand grenades', totaling 50 tons.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. delivers 50 tons of ammunition to Syria rebel groups |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/10/12/politics/syria-rebel-groups-ammunition-50-tons/index.html|accessdate=1 February 2016|date=12 October 2015}}</ref> However, statements from the US that the aid did not contain TOW's or anti-aircraft weapons made it clear that the U.S. continued to have serious regard for the interests of Turkey, which has warned against continued US support for the YPG. On the other hand, the US also supported Islamist rebel groups who fought the YPG. During the Battle of Aleppo, the US-backed [[Mountain Hawks Brigade]] battled the YPG and the [[Army of Revolutionaries]] for control of the village of [[Maryamin, Afrin|Maryamin]].<ref name=YPGallies>{{cite web |url= http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/ypg-and-allies-clashes-syrian-opposition-groups-aleppo-633986086|title= YPG, allies clash with Syrian opposition groups in Aleppo|date= 29 November 2015|publisher= Middle East Eye}}</ref>\n\nUS aid to the YPG continued in late October with the deployment of up to 50 US special forces to assist the YPG, and an enhanced air campaign to support the YPG and local militia groups in their fight against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]].<ref name=\"steele\">{{cite news |last=Steele |first=Jonathan |title=The Syrian Kurds are winning! |magazine=New York Review of Books |date=3 December 2015 |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/2015/12/03/syrian-kurds-are-winning/ |quote=Turkey had told ... the US that YPG forces would not be permitted to proceed beyond the Euphrates. In an apparent rebuke ... Kerry [said]: \"We\u2019re \u2026 enhancing our air campaign in order to help drive Da\u2019esh, which once dominated the Syria\u2013Turkey border, out of the last seventy-mile stretch...\u201d }} Review of ''Out of Nowhere: The Kurds of Syria in Peace and War'', by Michael M. Gunter.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Obama orders US special forces to 'assist' fight against Isis in Syria \u2019 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/30/syria-us-deployment-troops-obama-special-operations|accessdate=1 February 2016|date=30 October 2015}}</ref> Some of these special forces participated in the [[al-Shaddadi offensive (2016)]] and coordinated airstrikes against ISIL.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aftoBdrjm7Q|title=EXCLUSIVE: Interethnic coalition takes on the IS group in Syria|work=France 24 (Youtube)|date=22 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Battle of Tabqa (2017)]], [[Anti-Terror Units|YPG special forces]] were equipped with US-supplied [[combat helmet]]s, [[AN/PVS-7]] [[night vision device]]s, [[flashlight]]s, and were armed with [[M4 carbine]]s equipped with [[AN/PEQ-2]] [[laser sight]]s, [[holographic weapon sight]]s, and [[STANAG magazine]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.militarytimes.com/articles/syrian-kurds-ypg-us-military-weapons|title=Syrian Kurds are now armed with sensitive US weaponry, and the Pentagon denies supplying it|work=Military Times|author=Shawn Snow|date=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2017, it was announced by the Pentagon that American President [[Donald Trump]] approved of a plan that would have the United States directly provide heavy armaments to the major SDF component group, the YPG; the plan comes before a planned final offensive to capture Raqqa from ISIL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/09/us/politics/trump-kurds-syria-army.html|title=Trump to Arm Syrian Kurds, Even as Turkey Strongly Objects|work=New York Times|date=9 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/05/09/in-blow-to-u-s-turkey-ties-trump-administration-approves-plan-to-directly-arm-syrian-kurds-against-islamic-state/|title=In blow to U.S.-Turkey ties, Trump administration approves plan to arm Syrian Kurds against Islamic State|work=Washington Post|date=9 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/trump-oks-arms-syrian-kurds-turkish-objections-47304210|title=Trump OKs arms for Syrian Kurds, despite Turkish objections|work=ABC News|date=9 May 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509185346/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/trump-oks-arms-syrian-kurds-turkish-objections-47304210|archivedate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nBut there is also a break between American soldiers on the ground and the policy makers in Washington. The soldiers who interact with YPJ-YPG fighters regularly are more fully supportive of their Kurdish allies, and even began wearing patches with the YPG symbol on their American uniforms.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://jacobinmag.com/2018/04/syrian-kurds-rojava-trump-united-states-support|title=The Kurdish Dilemma|last=Hunt|first=Edward|website=jacobinmag.com|access-date=2018-12-05}}</ref> When officials heard of this development, however, the U.S soldiers were ordered to remove the patches. Unlike the soldiers, U.S officials see the YPJ-YPG as \"proxies\"<ref name=\":1\" /> rather than allies.\n\n==== Russia ====\n\nWith Russia's entrance into the war in late 2015 backing the Syrian government, some reports<!-- It is worth noting the source of the reports and their political affiliations in the Syrian Civil War.<ref> --> have reported that the YPG coordinated with or received weapons from Russia, with rival opposition groups stating that the timing and targeting of Russian airstrikes were \"suspiciously advantageous\" to the Kurdish militias.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-mideast-crisis-syria-kurds-idUKKCN0VW16Z|title=Britain says uneasy after evidence of Kurdish coordination with Syria and Russia|website=Reuters UK|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-03-19}}</ref>\n\nDespite this, YPG officials have said they did not cooperate with Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aranews.net/2015/12/kurdish-fighters-in-aleppo-deny-receiving-russian-military-support/|title=Kurdish fighters in Aleppo deny receiving Russian military support \u2013 ARA News|website=ARA News|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328015034/http://aranews.net/2015/12/kurdish-fighters-in-aleppo-deny-receiving-russian-military-support/|archivedate=28 March 2016}}</ref> However in July 2019, [[Rashid Abu Khawla]] the head of the [[Syrian Democratic Forces military councils#Deir ez-Zor|Syrian Democratic Forces' Deir ez-Zor Military Council]] stated that the Syrian Democratic Forces had cooperated with Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://npasyria.com/en/blog.php?id_blog=454&sub_blog=10&name_blog=Abu%20Khawla:%20We%20coordinate%20with%20Russia%20and%20I%20brought%20thousands%20of%20opposition%20fighters%20to%20our%20areas|title=Abu Khawla: We coordinate with Russia and I brought thousands of opposition fighters to our areas|website=npasyria.com}}</ref>\n\n===Diplomatic relations===\n{{See also|Foreign relations of Rojava}}\n\nRussia's position towards the YPG is not clear, and the US actively supports it, but their diplomatic relations with the PYD are the opposite. In January 2016 Russia pushed for the inclusion of the PYD in the Geneva talks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/260120161|title=Russia: Kurds should be included in Geneva talks |website=Rudaw|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref> The YPG would like to open a representative branch in the US, but in March 2016 interview its leader implied that it was not allowed to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kurdistantribune.com/2016/salih-muslim-time-has-proved-us-right/|title=Salih Muslim: Time Has Proved Us Right |website=The Kurdistan Tribune|language=en-US |quote=The West is fully aware that the Syrian Democratic Forces are an important and reliable active on the ground, hence the military support. Unfortunately, they have not yet approached us at a political level while they keep their ties with Saudi Arabia, Turkey ... However, we do hope political relations to materialize among us in the future.|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref>\n\nIn February, 2018, USA's [[Director of National Intelligence]] described YPG as the Syrian wing of PKK in its new report.<ref name=\"DNI2018\">[https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/os-dcoats-021318.PDF Director of National Intelligence, Worldwide threat assessment of the US intelligence community], 13 February 2018. Quote: \"The Kurdish People\u2019s Protection Unit\u2014the Syrian militia of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK)\u2014probably will seek some form of autonomy but will face resistance from Russia, Iran, and Turkey.\"</ref>\n\n=== International media outreach ===\n\nThe YPG's press office media operation has been a particular focus of its opponents, with [[Turkey]] bombing its premises in [[Cizire Canton]] in April 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-39708909|title=Turkey air strikes on Kurds in Syria and Iraq spark US concern|date=25 April 2017|work=BBC}}</ref> and the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) singling out its premises in [[Raqqa]] for a raid during the late stages of the [[Battle of Raqqa (2017)|Battle of Raqqa]] in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/sep/27/british-film-maker-killed-mehmet-aksoy-militants-raqqa-syria|title=British film-maker killed by Isis militants in Syria|date=27 September 2017|work=The Guardian|author=Matt Blake}}</ref>\n\n== Allegations concerning violations of international law and war crimes==\n{{See|\nHuman rights in the Democratic Federation of Northern Syria#DFNS-associated militias|Syrian Democratic Forces#Reported war crimes|Human rights violations during the Syrian Civil War#Syrian Democratic Forces|Human rights in Syria#Human rights in the Democratic Federation of Northern Syria}}\n\n=== Ethnic cleansing ===\n\nIn June 2015 the Turkish government stated that the YPG was carrying out an ethnic cleansing as part of a plan to join the Jazira and [[Koban\u00ee Canton|Koban\u00ee]] cantons into a single territory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Turkey accuses Kurdish forces of 'ethnic cleansing' in Syria|url=https://news.yahoo.com/turkey-accuses-kurdish-forces-ethnic-cleansing-syria-093148734.html|date=16 June 2015|agency=Agence France-Presse|quote=President Recep Tayyip Erdogan on Sunday said he was troubled by the advance of Kurdish forces, saying they could in the future create a structure to threaten Turkey.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]] reacted by starting an inquiry into the allegations.<ref name=\"Rudaw.net\">{{cite web|url=http://rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/14102015?keyword=amnesty|title=US voices concern over allegations of rights violations by YPG|date=14 October 2015|accessdate=20 October 2015 |last1=Saeed |first1=Yerevan |quote=We\u2019ll look closely at all these accusations to determine whether there's any veracity to the claims ... We call on those who actually are or will participate in administering these areas to do so inclusively and with respect for all groups regardless of ethnicity|website=[[Rudaw Media Network|Rudaw]] }}</ref> \n\nIn a report published by the [[United Nations]]' [[Independent International Commission of Inquiry on the Syrian Arab Republic]] on 10 March 2017, the Commission refuted Amnesty International's reports of ethnic cleansing, stating that \"'though allegations of 'ethnic cleansing' continued to be received during the period under review, the Commission found no evidence to substantiate reports that YPG or SDF forces ever targeted Arab communities on the basis of ethnicity.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://komnews.com/syria-and-islamist-groups-guilty-of-war-crimes-ypg-cleared-un-report/|title=Syria and Islamist groups guilty of war crimes, YPG cleared: UN report|work=Kom News|date=15 March 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317054645/https://komnews.com/syria-and-islamist-groups-guilty-of-war-crimes-ypg-cleared-un-report/|archivedate=17 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"UN report counters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/un-report-counters-amnesty-internationals-claim-that-kurds-are-ethnically-cleansing-in-syria/|title=UN report counters Amnesty International's claim that Kurds are ethnically cleansing in Syria|first=Paul|last=Antonopoulos|date=15 March 2017|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"refutes\">{{cite web|url=http://ekurd.net/ypg-changing-demographics-2017-03-14|title=UN report refutes ethnic cleansing claims against Syrian Kurdish YPG, SDF|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Forced displacement ===\n\nIn October 2015, [[Amnesty International]] published a report<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=In July and August 2015 Amnesty International investigated the forced displacement of residents from 10 villages and towns in areas under the control of the Autonomous Administration}}</ref> with reports that the YPG had driven at least 100 families from northern Syria and that in the villages of Asaylem and Husseiniya it had demolished resident homes. The report was made by Amnesty visiting the area contained in the report. It made local observations of destruction, and collected testimonies from former and actual residents of [[Al-Hasakah Governorate|al-Hasakeh]] and [[Raqqa Governorate|Raqqa]] governorates. It found cases of YPG fighters forcibly displacing residents and using fire and bulldozers to raze homes and other structures.<ref name=\"amnesty.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2015/10/syria-us-allys-razing-of-villages-amounts-to-war-crimes|title=Syria: US ally\u2019s razing of villages amounts to war crimes|work=Amnesty International|date=13 October 2015|accessdate=17 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite news |date=13 October 2015 |title=Syria Kurds 'razing villages seized from IS' \u2013 Amnesty |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-34511134|agency=[[BBC News]] |quote=Of 225 buildings visible [in Husseiniya] in June 2014, only 14 were still standing by June 2015. }}</ref>\n\nForced displacement of civilians and destruction of civilian property is not a war crime per se. These acts only become a war crime when there is no \"imperative military necessity\" for them. Amnesty International stated the report documents cases in which there was no such justification.<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=this report documents cases in which there was no such justification}}</ref> It furthermore states that \"the circumstances of some of these displacements suggested that they were carried out in retaliation for people's perceived sympathies with, or family ties to, suspected members of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] or other armed groups\",<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=The circumstances of some of the instances of forced displacement documented in this report suggest that they were carried out in retaliation for people's perceived sympathies with, or family ties to, suspected members of IS or other armed groups. This would constitute collective punishment, which is a violation of international humanitarian law.}}</ref> thus constituting \"collective punishment, which is a violation of international humanitarian law\".\n\nIn interviews, YPG spokespersons acknowledged that a number of families were in fact displaced. However, they placed the number at no more than 25,<ref>{{Citation|last=Amnesty International|title=\"We had nowhere else to go\": Forced displacement and demolitions in northern Syria|date=2015-10-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LlOzoCHaNeM&t=2m10s|accessdate=2016-03-19}}</ref> and stated military necessity. They stated that the family members of terrorists maintained communications with them, and therefore had to be removed from areas where they might pose a danger.<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=In some dangerous areas there are some specific cases that are very small, resulting from the terrorist threat, where families were sent away from the area ... Only 25 families were forced to leave across Rojava ... (They are told) 'Folks, remove your things please, and if you leave from this area until the war ends it will be a good thing ...' You have terrorists in al-Raqqa and their families \u2013 the uncle, and brother, and sister \u2013 are here, and they are in communication, giving them information. We were forced to distance these families. Not detain them. Distance them. Take them outside of the area.}}</ref> They further stated that ISIL was using civilians in those areas to plant car bombs or carry out other attacks on the YPG.<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=He added that IS was benefiting from the presence of civilians in these areas, and using them to plant car bombs or carry out other attacks on the YPG.}}</ref> By describing the events in Hammam al-Turkman before the village was evacuated, the Amnesty International report itself inadvertently supports these YPG reports of military necessity.<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=After the YPG took the village, on 15 June, a car bomb killed three YPG fighters 4&nbsp;km from Hammam al-Turkman at a checkpoint in Damishli. The following day there were skirmishes between the YPG and IS in the village before IS was pushed back. A second car bomb went off at a YPG checkpoint at the health clinic in the village on 18 June killing a YPG fighter and injuring one civilian and three days later IS shot and killed a second YPG fighter near the clinic. It was after the death of this fighter that the residents were told by the YPG that they had to leave the village.}}</ref>\n\n=== Recruitment of minors ===\n\nIn June 2014, [[Human Rights Watch]] criticized the YPG for accepting minors into their ranks,<ref name=\"hrw\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/en/world-report-2009/china |title=World Report 2009: China|publisher=Human Rights Watch |accessdate=14 July 2009}}</ref> picking up on multiple earlier reports of teenage fighters serving in the YPG, with a report by the [[United Nations]] [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary General]] stating that 24 minors under age of 18 had been recruited by YPG, with 124 having been recruited by the Free Syrian Army and 5 by the Syrian Arab Army.<ref name=\"children\">{{cite report |author=[[United Nations Security Council|U.N. Security Council]] |date=5 June 2015 |title=Report of the Secretary-General: Children and armed conflict |url=https://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A/69/926 |at=para. 191 |quote=Actual numbers are expected to be higher.... A number of pro-Government groups, including Hizbullah, also reportedly recruited children in small numbers.}}</ref> In response, the YPG and YPJ signed the [[Geneva Call]] ''Deed of Commitment'' protecting children in armed conflict, prohibiting sexual violence and against gender discrimination in July 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/syrian-arab-republic/syria-4-brigades-free-syrian-army-commit-prohibit-sexual-violence-and|title=Syria: 4 brigades of the Free Syrian Army commit to prohibit sexual violence and the use of child soldiers [EN/AR] - Syrian Arab Republic}}</ref> and Kurdish security forces (YPG and [[Asayish (Syria)|Asayish]]) began receiving human rights training from [[Geneva Call]] and other international organisations with the YPG pledging publicly to demobilize all fighters under 18 within a month and began to enact disciplinary measures against commanders of the units that had involved in corruption and accepting recruit under age of 18 to their ranks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Syria: Kurdish Forces Violating Child Soldier Ban Despite Promises, Children Still Fight|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/07/10/syria-kurdish-forces-violating-child-soldier-ban-0|website=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Perry |first1=Tom |last2=Malla |first2=Naline |date=10 September 2015 |title=Western states train Kurdish force in Syria, force's leader says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/09/10/uk-mideast-crisis-syria-kurds-idUKKCN0RA1MO20150910 |agency=[[Reuters]] |quote=Amnesty International this month faulted the Kurdish administration for arbitrary detentions and unfair trials.... [Ciwan] Ibrahim said ... efforts were underway to improve its human rights record.... The Geneva Call ... promotes good treatment of civilians in war zones... }}</ref> In October 2015 the YPG demobilized 21 minors from the military service in its ranks.<ref name=\"Demobilized children\">{{cite report |date=28 October 2015 |title=YPG demobilizes 21 children under the age of 18 from the military service in its ranks |url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/2015/10/ypg-demobilizes-21-children-under-the-age-of-18-from-the-military-service-in-its-ranks/ |publisher=[[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121223140/http://supportkurds.org/news/wednesday-28-october-2015/ |archivedate=2015-11-21 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Human Rights Watch<ref>{{cite web|title=Syria: Armed Group Recruiting Children in Camps|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2018/08/03/syria-armed-group-recruiting-children-camps|website=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> and the annual UN report of 2018,<ref>{{cite report |url=http://undocs.org/s/2018/465|author=[[United Nations Security Council|U.N. Security Council]] |date=16 May 2018 |title=Report of the Secretary-General: Children and armed conflict |access-date=23 October 2019 }}</ref> there were 224 cases of child recruitment by the YPG and its women's unit, the YPJ, in 2017, an almost fivefold increase from the previous year.  This sparked immediate conversations with the anti-child-recruitment [[NGO]] [[Geneva Call]] which resulted in a broad new military directive strictly prohibiting all recruitment of persons under 18, ordering that any such persons within SDF be immediately removed from the payroll and transferred to the custody of the civilian Authority For Education, mandating the appointment of an [[ombudsman]] in each military service to receive and investigate reports of child recruitment, and ordering punitive measures by military police and by the SDF's Military Discipline Department against anyone found to be responsible for child recruitment. [[Geneva Call]] immediately praised the SDF's wide-ranging initiative to eliminate and prevent child recruitment throughout all of SDF's military organizations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/380c0f07-bd15-4d0b-b57b-1cd23b7bf977 |title=SDF command issues order banning child recruitment |date=7 September 2018  |access-date=23 October 2019 |publisher=Kurdistan24 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Asia|War}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[International Freedom Battalion]]\n* [[The Medal for the Martyrs]]\n* [[Jabhat al-Akrad]]\n* [[Kurdistan Workers' Party]] (PKK)\n* [[Party of Free Life of Kurdistan]] (PJAK)\n* [[Peshmerga]]\n* [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]]\n* [[Sutoro]]\n* [[YPG\u2013FSA relations]]\n* [[YPG\u2013Syrian government conflict]]\n* [[List of armed groups in the Syrian Civil War]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book\n|last=Rashid\n|first=Bedir Mulla\n|translator=Obaida Hitto\n|title= Military and Security Structures of the Autonomous Administration in Syria\n|url=http://omranstudies.org/publications/reports/download/68_d403f01ed28320cb2e67b13cffb381c7.html\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701140230/http://omranstudies.org/publications/reports/download/68_d403f01ed28320cb2e67b13cffb381c7.html\n|url-status=dead\n|archive-date=2018-07-01\n|orig-year=1st pub. 2017\n|date= 2018\n|publisher= Omran for Strategic Studies\n|location= [[Istanbul]]\n|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Facebook|RojavaDefenseUnits|name=People's Defense Units YPG}}\n{{Syrian Kurdistan topics}}\n{{Kurdish nationalist organisations}}\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n\n[[Category:Apoist organizations in Syria]]\n[[Category:People's Protection Units| ]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in Syria]]\n[[Category:Kurdistan Communities Union]]\n[[Category:Syrian Kurdish organizations]]\n[[Category:Irregular units and formations]]\n[[Category:Democratic Federation of Northern Syria]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2011]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|YPG}}\n{{distinguish|Women's Protection Units}}\n{{short description|Mainly-Kurdish militia in Syria}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = People's Protection Units\n| native_name = {{lang|ku|Yek\u00eeney\u00ean Parastina Gel (YPG)}} <br />{{rtl-lang|ar|{{rlm}}\u0648\u062d\u062f\u0627\u062a \u062d\u0645\u0627\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0628{{lrm}}{{lrm}}}}\n| image = People's Protection Units Flag.svg\n| caption = Flag of the YPG\n| dates = 2011\u2013present\n| allegiance = {{flagicon image|Flag of the Kurdish Supreme Committee.svg}} [[Kurdish Supreme Committee]] (2011\u20132013)<ref name=casualties/><br/>{{flag|Rojava}} (2013\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/13112013|title=PYD announces surprise interim government in Syria's Kurdish regions|publisher=[[Rudaw Media Network|Rudaw]]|accessdate=9 October 2014|date=13 November 2013}}</ref><br />\n{{flagicon image|Flag_of_the_Democratic_Union_Party.svg}} [[Democratic Union Party (Syria)|Democratic Union Party]] (2011\u2013present)\n| type = [[Light infantry]] militia with several [[Technical (vehicle)|motorised]] battalions\n| size = 35 000 {{small|(Including YPJ, 2017 estimate)}}{{sfnp|Rashid|2018|p=16}}\n| command_structure = {{flagicon image|Flag of Syrian Democratic Forces.svg}} [[Syrian Democratic Forces]]<!-- affects the field \"Part of\"-->\n| garrison_label = Garrison\n| motto = ''YPG dime\u015fe, erd \u00fb ezman diheje'' (YPG is marching, and the earth and sky [''or'' heavens] tremble)\n| march = \n| battles = [[Syrian Civil War]]\n* [[Rojava conflict#YPG claims territory|2012 Rojava campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Aleppo (2012\u2013present)|Battle of Aleppo]]\n** [[Northern Aleppo offensive (2016)]]\n* [[Al-Hasakah Governorate campaign (2012\u201313)]]\n** [[Battle of Ras al-Ayn]]\n** [[Battle of al-Yaarubiyah]]\n* [[Battle of Tell Abyad (2013)]]\n* [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]]\n* [[Al-Hasakah offensive (February\u2013March 2015)|Al-Hasakah offensive]]\n* [[Battle of Sarrin (June\u2013July 2015)|Battle of Sarrin]]\n* [[Tell Abyad offensive]]\n* [[Battle of Al-Hasakah (June\u2013August 2015)|Battle of Al-Hasakah]]\n* [[Al-Hawl offensive]]\n* [[Tishrin Dam offensive]]\n* [[Al-Shaddadi offensive (2016)|Al-Shaddadi offensive]]\n* [[Battle of Tell Abyad (2016)]]\n* [[Northern Raqqa offensive (May 2016)|Northern Raqqa offensive]]\n* [[Manbij offensive]]\n* [[Battle of al-Hasakah (2016)]]\n* [[Western al-Bab offensive (October\u2013November 2016)]]\n* [[Raqqa campaign (2016\u20132017)]]\n* [[Turkish military operation in Afrin]]\n* [[Eastern Syria Insurgency]]\n* [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria]]\n[[Iraqi Civil War (2014\u20132017)|Iraqi Civil War]]\n* [[December 2014 Sinjar offensive|2014 Sinjar offensive]]\n* [[November 2015 Sinjar offensive|2015 Sinjar offensive]]\n<!--Commanders-->| website = {{Official website|https://www.ypgrojava.org/}}\n| commander1 = S\u00eepan Hemo\n| commander1_label = General Commander\n| commander2 = Nuri Mahmoud\n| commander2_label = Spokesperson\n| notable_commanders = Ciwan \u00cebrah\u00eem\n<!-- Insignia -->| identification_symbol = \n| identification_symbol_label = Emblem\n| identification_symbol_2 = [[File:YPG Insignia.svg|150px]]\n| identification_symbol_2_label = Insignia\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Campaignbox Rojava Revolution}}\n[[File:Syrian civil war 01 11 2015.png|thumb|Military situation in the Syrian Civil War in November 2015]]\n[[File:Syrian civil war 01 11 2018.png|thumb|Military situation in January 2019]]\n\nThe '''People's Protection Units''' or '''People's Defense Units''' ({{lang-ku|\u06cc\u06d5\u06a9\u06cc\u0646\u06d5\u06a9\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u067e\u0627\u0631\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0646\u06cc \u06af\u06d5\u0644 |Yek\u00eeney\u00ean Parastina Gel}} ('''YPG''') {{IPA-ku|j\u025bki\u02d0n\u025bje\u02d0n p\u0251\u02d0\u027e\u0251\u02d0st\u026fn\u0251\u02d0 \u0261\u025bl|pron}}; {{lang-ar|\u0648\u062d\u062f\u0627\u062a \u062d\u0645\u0627\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0628|Wa\u1e25d\u0101t \u1e24im\u0101yat a\u0161-\u0160a\u02bdb}}; {{lang-syc|\u071a\u0715\u071d\u0308\u0718\u072c\u0710 \u0715\u0723\u0718\u072c\u072a\u0710 \u0715\u0725\u0721\u0710|translit=\u1e24doywotho d'Sutoro d'Amo}}) is a mainly-[[Kurds in Syria|Kurdish]] militia in Syria and the primary component of the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/ascent-of-the-pyd-and-the-sdf |title=Ascent of the PYD and the SDF |last1=Barfi |first1=Barak |date=April 2016 |publisher=Washington Institute for Near East Policy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2016/02/kurds-turkey-pkk-ypg/470991/|title=Who Exactly Are 'the Kurds'?|first=Steven A.|last=Cook|work=The Atlantic |accessdate=16 February 2017|date=25 February 2016}}</ref> The YPG mostly consists of ethnic [[Kurdish people|Kurds]], but also includes Arabs and [[Foreign fighters in the Syrian and Iraqi Civil Wars|foreign volunteers]]; it is closely allied to the [[Syriac Military Council]], a militia of [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]]. The YPG was formed in 2011 . It expanded rapidly in the [[Syrian Civil War]] and came to predominate over other armed Kurdish groups. A sister group, the [[Women's Protection Units]] (YPJ), fights alongside them. The YPG is active in [[Rojava|Northern and Eastern Syria]].\n\nIn early 2015, the group won a major victory over the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) during the [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]], where the YPG began to receive air and ground support from the United States and other [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve]] militaries. Since then, the YPG has primarily fought against ISIL, as well as on occasion fighting other [[Syrian opposition|Syrian rebel groups]] and the [[Turkish Armed Forces]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/kurdish-forces-bolster-assad-in-aleppo|title=Kurdish Forces Bolster Assad in Aleppo|publisher=Washington Institute|language=en|access-date=2017-03-17 |date=29 July 2016}}</ref> In late 2015, the YPG founded the SDF, as an umbrella group to better incorporate Arabs and [[Sectarianism and minorities in the Syrian Civil War|minorities]] into the war effort. In 2016\u20132017, the SDF's [[Raqqa campaign (2016\u20132017)|Raqqa campaign]] led to the liberation of the city of [[Raqqa]], the Islamic State's ''de facto'' capital. Several western sources have described the YPG as the \"most effective\" force in fighting ISIL in Syria.<ref>{{cite news|title=Turkey v Syria's Kurds v Islamic State|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-33690060|agency=BBC|date=23 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=US troops wearing YPG patches in Syria|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/us-soldiers-ypg-patches-syria-2016-5|work=Business Insider|date=27 May 2016}}</ref> A [[light infantry]] force, the YPG has limited military equipment and few [[armoured vehicles]].\n\n== History ==\n\n===2004: Early origins===\nKurdish youth attempted to unify themselves following the [[2004 Qamishli riots]]. The riots began as clashes between rivaling football fans before taking a political turn, with Arab fans raising pictures of [[Saddam Hussein]] while the Kurdish fans reportedly proclaimed \"We will sacrifice our lives for Bush\". This resulted in clashes between the two groups who attacked each other with sticks, stones and knives. Government security forces entered the city to quell the riot, firing at the crowds. The riots resulted in around 36 dead, most of them Kurds.\n\nThey did not, however, emerge as a significant force until the [[Syrian Civil War]] erupted in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=UA 15/05 Torture and ill-treatment/ possible unfair trial |url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/88000/mde240032005en.pdf |website=amnesty.org}}</ref><ref name=\"Vice\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/read/meet-the-ypg|title=Meet the YPG, the Kurdish militia that doesn't want help from anyone|last=Gold|first=Danny|date=31 October 2012|quote=A member of YPG\u2019s central command \u2026 said that the YPG formed in 2004 shortly after the Qamishlo riots, when a number of Kurdish youth realized that they needed to be able to defend themselves more efficiently. They did not officially declare themselves until the revolution started in 2011.|magazine=[[Vice (magazine)|VICE]]|accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011: Establishment ===\nExisting underground Kurdish political parties, namely the [[Democratic Union Party (Syria)|Democratic Union Party]] (PYD) and the [[Kurdish National Council]] (KNC), joined to form the [[Kurdish Supreme Committee]] (KSC) and established the People's Protection Units (YPG) militia to defend Kurdish-inhabited areas in northern Syria.<ref>{{cite web |last1=YPG |title=About Us |url=https://www.ypgrojava.org/About-Us |website=ypgrojava.org |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=casualties>{{cite news|title=Armed Kurds Surround Syrian Security Forces in Qamishli |url=http://www.rudaw.net/english/news/syria/4984.html |accessdate=27 July 2012 |publisher=Rudaw |date=22 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724224808/http://www.rudaw.net/english/news/syria/4984.html |archivedate=24 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===July 2012: Control of Kurdish areas===\nIn July 2012, the YPG had a standoff with Syrian government forces in the Kurdish city of [[Koban\u00ee]] and the surrounding areas. After negotiations, government forces withdrew and the YPG took control of [[Koban\u00ee]], [[Amuda]], and [[Afrin, Syria|Afrin]].<ref name=casualties/><ref>{{cite news|title=Kurds Give Ultimatum to Syrian Security Forces|url=http://www.ekurd.net/mismas/articles/misc2012/7/syriakurd541.htm |accessdate=9 October 2014|publisher=Rudaw|date=21 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nBy December 2012, it had expanded to 8 [[Brigade (military)|brigades]], which were formed in [[Qamishlo]], [[Koban\u00ee]], and [[Ras al-Ayn]] (Ser\u00ea Kaniy\u00ea) and in the districts of [[Afrin District|Afrin]], [[Al-Malikiyah District|al-Malikiyah]], and [[Al-Bab District|al-Bab]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://scientiahumana.org/2012/12/04/the-kurdish-protection-units-have-formed-a-new-brigade-in-the-al-bab-region |title=The Kurdish Protection Units have formed a new brigade in the Al\u2013Bab region |work=Scientia Humana |date=4 December 2012 |accessdate=18 December 2013 |quote=Kurdish Information Center |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108025429/http://scientiahumana.org/2012/12/04/the-kurdish-protection-units-have-formed-a-new-brigade-in-the-al-bab-region |archivedate=8 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Late 2012: Islamist attacks make YPG dominant===\nThe YPG did not initially take an offensive posture in the Syrian Civil War. Aiming mostly to defend Kurdish-majority areas, it avoided engaging Syrian government forces, which still controlled several enclaves in Kurdish territory. The YPG changed this policy when Ras al-Ayn was taken by the [[al-Qaeda]]-affiliated [[al-Nusra Front]]. At first the YPG conquered the surrounding government-controlled areas: [[al-Darbasiyah]] (Kurdish: Dirb\u00eas\u00ee), [[Tel Tamer]] and [[al-Malikiyah]] (Kurdish: D\u00earika Hemko) in order to prevent the FSA from gaining more power in the area.{{Citation needed|date=March 2016}} The subsequent [[Battle of Ras al-Ayn]] started in earnest when on 19 November 2012, the al-Nusra Front and a second al-Qaeda affiliate, [[Ghuraba al-Sham]], attacked Kurdish positions in the town. The battle ended with a YPG victory in July 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/2/8/76750/World/Region/Kurds-expel-jihadists-from-flashpoint-Syrian-town-.aspx |title=Kurds expel jihadists from flashpoint Syrian town: NGO|agency=AFP|work=Al-Ahram Weekly|date=17 July 2013|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhile many rebel groups clashed with the YPG, [[jihadist]] and [[Salafist]] groups did so the most often.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |author=International Crisis Group |title=Flight of Icarus? The PYD\u2019s Precarious Rise in Syria |date=8 May 2014 |quote=While rebel groups from across the ideological spectrum have clashed with the PYD, jihadi and Salafi groups have done so most aggressively and consistently |accessdate=20 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220181554/http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |archive-date=20 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The YPG proved to be the only Kurdish militia able to effectively resist the fundamentalists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rudaw.net/english/interview/22072013 |title=YPG Commander: Kurds Are Bulwark Against Islamic Extremism in Syria|publisher=Rudaw|accessdate=9 October 2014|date=22 July 2013}}</ref> While the YPG protected the Kurdish communities it was able to extract a price: it prevented the emergence of new, rival militias and forced existing ones to cooperate with or join the YPG forces on its terms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |author=International Crisis Group |title=Flight of Icarus? The PYD\u2019s Precarious Rise in Syria |date=8 May 2014 |quote=The PYD\u2019s growing influence largely has come at the expense of other Kurdishgroups. In particular, it has prevented emergence of new, rival militias while forcing existing ones to cooperate with or join PYD forces on their terms |accessdate=20 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220181554/http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |archive-date=20 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This was how the Islamist attacks enabled the YPG to unite the Syrian Kurds under its banner<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf|author=International Crisis Group|title=Flight of Icarus? The PYD\u2019s Precarious Rise in Syria|date=8 May 2014|quote=Crisis Group interview, Erbil, 4 July 2013: Intensified Islamist attacks in Kurdish areas shifted Kurdish public opinion toward the PYD. A resident of Tell Tamr, a partly Kurdish town targeted by armed Islamist groups, said, \"in the aftermath of the battle of Ras al-Ayn, Islamists entered Tell Tamr. They began kidnapping and killing Kurds. I am not a YPG supporter, and I will never be. But if it weren\u2019t for the YPG, not a single Kurd would be left in the [al-] Jazeera region\". Crisis Group interview, Erbil, July 2013. A journalist working for a pro-KDP channel commented: \"I was the most critical person against the PYD. But at the moment, I have to admit that they are saving the people from the worst\".|accessdate=20 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220181554/http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf|archive-date=20 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and caused<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |author=International Crisis Group |title=Flight of Icarus? The PYD\u2019s Precarious Rise in Syria |date=8 May 2014 |quote=\"At the same time, Ankara turned a blind eye to the Islamist fighters crossing from Turkey into Syria, viewing them \u2013 in addition to helping bring down the Assad regime \u2013 as potential counterweights to the PYD. The strategy backfired; the PYD not only gained territory, but also bolstered its appeal among Kurds as their only protector from jihadis. In September 2013, a Turkish official acknowledged: 'We made the PYD stronger by trying to undermine it'\" |accessdate=20 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220181554/http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/Middle%20East%20North%20Africa/Iraq%20Syria%20Lebanon/Syria/151-flight-of-icarus-the-pyd-s-precarious-rise-in-syria.pdf |archive-date=20 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> it to become the de facto army of the Syrian Kurds.<ref name=\"bb\">{{cite book|last1=N. Abboud|first1=Samer|title=Syria|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-7456-9801-4|page=116|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BPbrCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT116}}</ref><ref name=\"nn\">{{cite news|title=Kurdish Woman Leading Battle Against Islamic State in Kobane: Activists|url=http://www.ndtv.com/world-news/kurdish-woman-leading-battle-against-islamic-state-in-kobane-activists-678354|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"aus\">{{cite news|title=Woman leads Kurds in battle against Islamic State in Kobane: activists|url=http://www.smh.com.au/world/woman-leads-kurds-in-battle-against-islamic-state-in-kobane-activists-20141013-1158kr.html|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"enalb\">{{cite news|title=Kurdish woman leads fight against ISIS in Kobane|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/2014/10/14/Kurdish-woman-leads-fight-against-ISIS-in-Kobane-.html|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2013: Kurdish control of al-Yaarubiyah/Til Ko\u00e7er===\n{{main|Battle of al-Yaarubiyah}}\nIn October 2013, YPG fighters took control of [[al-Yaarubiyah]] (Til Ko\u00e7er) following intense clashes with ISIL. The clashes lasted about three days, with the Til Ko\u00e7er border gate to Iraq being taken in a major offensive launched on the night of 24 October.<ref name=\"til\" /> PYD leader Saleh Muslim told St\u00eark TV that this success created an alternative against efforts to hold the territory under embargo,<ref name=\"til\">{{cite news|url=http://en.firatajans.com/news/news/ypg-takes-control-of-til-kocer.htm |title=YPG takes control of Til Ko\u00e7er |date=27 October 2013 |agency=[[Firat News Agency]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209152741/http://en.firatajans.com/news/news/ypg-takes-control-of-til-kocer.htm |archivedate=9 December 2013}}</ref> referring to the fact that the other border crossings with Iraq led to areas controlled by the [[Kurdistan Regional Government]], while al-Yaarubiyah led to areas controlled by the Iraqi central government.\n\n===2014: Fight against ISIL===\n[[File:Rojava february 2014.png|250px|thumb|YPG-controlled territory, February 2014]]\nIn 2014, the [[Syriac Military Council]], a group of [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] units, was formally integrated into the YPG's command structure.\n\nThe [[inter-rebel conflict during the Syrian Civil War]] led to open war between the [[Free Syrian Army]] and ISIL in January 2014. The YPG collaborated with FSA groups to fight ISIL in [[Raqqa Governorate|Raqqa]] province;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aranews.net/2014/05/fsa-and-ypg-cooperate-against-isil-militants-in-syrias-tel-abyad/|title=FSA and YPG cooperate against ISIL militants in Syria's Tel Abyad|date=12 May 2014|publisher=ARA News|accessdate=9 October 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008154840/http://aranews.net/2014/05/fsa-and-ypg-cooperate-against-isil-militants-in-syrias-tel-abyad/|archivedate=8 October 2014}}</ref> the group also formed an operations room with multiple FSA factions, called [[Euphrates Volcano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aranews.net/2014/09/ypg-fsa-form-joint-military-chamber-combat-isis-syria/|title=YPG and FSA form a joint military chamber to combat ISIS in Syria|publisher=ARA News|date=12 September 2014|accessdate=9 October 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014063318/http://aranews.net/2014/09/ypg-fsa-form-joint-military-chamber-combat-isis-syria/|archivedate=14 October 2014}}</ref> However, the general outcome of this campaign was a massive advance by ISIL, which effectively separated the eastern part of Rojava from the main force of FSA rebels. ISIL followed up on its success by attacking the YPG and the FSA in Koban\u00ee Canton in March and fighting its way to the gates of the city of Koban\u00ee in September.\nThe actual [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]] approximately coincided with an escalation in the [[American-led intervention in Syria]]. This intervention had started with aiding the FSA against the government, but when the FSA was getting defeated by ISIL in eastern Syria, it escalated to bombing ISIL on Syrian territory.\n\nWith the world fearing another massacre in Koban\u00ee, American support increased substantially. The US gave intense [[close air support]] to the YPG, and in doing so, started military cooperation with one of the factions. While it expected that ISIL would quickly crush the YPG and the FSA, this alliance was not considered a problem for the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/10/08/world/meast/isis-threat/index.html |title=U.S. military: Airstrikes against ISIS won't save key city of Kobani|date=9 October 2014|publisher=CNN |accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref> The YPG won the battle in early 2015.\n\nMeanwhile, the situation had been stable in Afrin and Aleppo. The fight between the FSA and ISIL had led to a normalization in the relations between FSA and YPG since the end of 2013. In February 2015, the YPG signed a judicial agreement with the [[Levant Front]] in [[Aleppo Governorate|Aleppo]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=KURDISH YPG AND JABHAT AL-SHAMIYA AGREEMENT ON JUDICIARY COOPERATION IN ALEPPO|url=https://www.facebook.com/SyrianRebellionObservatory/photos/a.1648239072069399.1073741828.1648217982071508/1699722200254419/?type=1 |date=5 February 2015|publisher=Syrian Rebellion Observatory}}</ref><!--allys-->\n\n===Spring 2015: Offensive operations with coalition support===\n[[File:Rojava june 2015.png|250px|thumb|YPG-controlled territory, June 2015]]\nIn the spring 2015, [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] was close to capturing the Iraqi city of [[Battle of Ramadi (2014\u201315)|Ramadi]].{{Relevance inline|date=March 2017}} The YPG was able and willing to offensively engage and put pressure on ISIL and had built up a track record as a reliable military partner of the US. With American close air support, offensives near [[Eastern al-Hasakah offensive|Hasakah]] and from Hasakah [[Western al-Hasakah offensive|westward]] culminated in the [[Tell Abyad offensive|conquest of Tell Abyad]], linking up Koban\u00ee with Hasakah in July 2015.\n\nWith these offensives, the YPG had begun to make advances into areas that did not always have a Kurdish majority. When the YPG and the FSA entered the border town of [[Tell Abyad]] in June 2015, parts of the population fled the intense fighting and the airstrikes.<ref name=\"pitarakis\">{{cite news|last1=Pitarakis|first1=Lefteris|last2=Mroue|first2=Bassem|date=14 June 2015|title=Thousands of Syrians flee into Turkey amid intense fighting|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/7f62663318e94589bf6097825914a088/kurds-nearing-key-islamic-state-held-syrian-border-town |agency=AP|quote=Thousands of Syrians cut through a border fence and crossed over into Turkey \u2026 fleeing intense fighting \u2026 between Kurdish fighters and jihadis.}}</ref>\n\n===Autumn 2015: foundation of the SDF===\nThe [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] was established in Hasakah on 11 October 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/10/17/turkey-claim-syrian-kurds-terrorists-not-isis-ypg-pkk-sdf/|title=Why Is Turkey Fighting Syria's Kurds?|last=Abadi|first=Cameron|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref><ref name=\"KQ1015\">{{cite web|url=http://kurdishquestion.com/index.php/kurdistan/west-kurdistan/declaration-of-establishment-by-democratic-syria-forces/1179-declaration-of-establishment-by-democratic-syria-forces.html|title=Declaration of establishment by Syrian Democratic Forces|date=15 October 2015|publisher=Kurdish Question|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224085811/http://kurdishquestion.com/index.php/kurdistan/west-kurdistan/declaration-of-establishment-by-democratic-syria-forces/1179-declaration-of-establishment-by-democratic-syria-forces.html|archive-date=24 February 2016|accessdate=15 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It has its origins in the YPG-FSA collaboration against ISIL, which had previously led to the establishment of the [[Euphrates Volcano|Euphrates Volcano joint operations room]] in 2014. Many of the partners are the same, and even the logo / flag with the Blue Euphrates symbol has common traits with that of Euphrates Volcano. The primary difference is that Euphrates Volcano was limited to coordinating the activities of independent Kurdish and Arab groups, while the SDF is a single organisation made up of Kurds, Arabs, and [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]].\n\nThe first success of the SDF was the capture of the strategic ethnically Arab town of al-Hawl from ISIL during the [[2015 Al-Hawl offensive|al-Hawl offensive]] in November 2015. This was followed in December by the [[Tishrin Dam offensive]]. The dam was captured on 26 December. Participating forces included the YPG, the FSA group [[Army of Revolutionaries]], the tribal group [[al-Sanadid Forces]] and the Assyrian [[Syriac Military Council]]. The coalition had some heavy weapons and was supported by intense US led airstrikes.<ref name=\"reuters-alliance\">{{cite news |date=28 December 2015 |title=U.S.-backed alliance captures key dam from Islamic State \u2013 alliance spokesman |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-mideast-crisis-syria-alliance-idUKKBN0U90DC20151228 |agency=[[Reuters]] |quote=Colonel Talal Selo ... said the rapid advance overnight by thousands of troops from the Democratic Forces of Syria had brought the dam ... under their control on Saturday.... Selo said ... the latest round of fighting ... involved several thousand fighters from the Democratic Forces of Syria with heavy armour. }}</ref> The capture of the hydroelectric dam also had positive effects on the [[economy of Rojava]].<ref name=\"Themedialine\">{{cite news |date=1 February 2016 |title= Photos of Tishrin Dam, Liberated from ISIS |url=http://www.themedialine.org/views/blog/photos-of-tishrin-dam-liberated-from-isis/ |quote=Tishrin is an incredible dam, not least of all because of the fact that it sits cradled in a beautiful lush valley, in an otherwise dry and arid land. But also because of what Tishrin implies for the people of Rojava who have survived for the past two years under incredible economic and political conditions, exacerbated significantly by lack of access to water and electricity which Tishrin provides.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Claimed and de facto territory of Rojava.png|thumb|210px|SDF-controlled territory (green), claimed territory (orange), [[Turkish occupation of northern Syria|Turkish-occupied Afrin]] (red) in October 2018]]\n\n===2016===\nIn February, the YPG-led SDF launched the [[Al-Shaddadi offensive (2016)|al-Shaddadi offensive]], followed by the [[Manbij offensive]] in May, and [[Raqqa offensive (2016\u2013present)|the Raqqa]] and [[Aleppo offensive (November\u2013December 2016)|Aleppo offensives]] in November. These operations extended SDF-controlled territory, usually at ISIL's expense.\n\nOn 7 April 2016, the Kurdish neighborhood of [[Sheikh Maqsood]] in Aleppo was shelled with [[Mortar (weapon)|mortars]] that may have contained [[List of chemical warfare agents|chemical agents]] (160 killed or wounded).<ref>{{cite web|title=MAPPING MILITANT ORGANIZATIONS: Jaish al-Islam|url=https://web.stanford.edu/group/mappingmilitants/cgi-bin/groups/view/533|website=Stanford University|date=31 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.com/en/concerns-grow-about-abuses-war-crimes-in-syria/a-19277777 |title= Middle East Concerns grow about abuses, war crimes in Syria |work=Deutsche Welle|date=25 May 2016}}</ref> Spokesperson for the YPG said that [[Saudi Arabia]]-backed [[Jaysh al-Islam]] (Army of Islam) rebel group has attacked the Kurdish neighborhood of Aleppo with \"forbidden weapons\" many times since the war's start.<ref>\"[http://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/7a0f6294-ab7f-4d15-b5af-3ff4b444ab3f/Syrian-rebels-admit-chemical-use-against-Kurds Syrian rebels admit chemical use against Kurds]\". [[Kurdistan 24]]. 9 April 2016.</ref>\n\n===2018: Turkish military intervention===\n{{See also|Turkish military intervention in Syria (January 2018\u2013present)}}\n\n== Women's Protection Units ==\n{{main|Women's Protection Units}}\n[[File:YPJ fighters shake hands with one another.jpg|thumb|Women's Protection Units in November 2014]]\nThe [[Women's Protection Units]] (YPJ), also known as the Women's Defense Units, is the YPG's female brigade, which was set up in 2012. Kurdish media have said that YPJ troops became vital during the [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Trieb|first1=Erin|title=Meet the Kurdish Women Fighting ISIS in Syria|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/isis-terror/meet-kurdish-women-fighting-isis-syria-n199821|accessdate=19 March 2016|agency=NBC News|date=August 2014}}</ref> Consisting of approximately 20,000 fighters, they make up around 40% of the YPG.<ref name=\"profil\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/profil-rojda-felat-1.3239571|title=Profil - Rojda Felat. Kommandeurin der Offensive gegen den IS in Raqqa und Bismarck-Fan. [Profile - Rojda Felat. Commander of the offensive against the IS in Raqqa and Bismarck-Fan]|publisher=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]]|language=German|author=Moritz Baumstieger|date=9 November 2016|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref> {{Dubious|date=August 2019}}\n\n== Organization ==\n\n=== Flags ===\n{{multiple image\n | align = center\n | total_width = 600\n | header = Flags of the People's Protection Units\n \n | image1 = People's Protection Units Flag (2011-2012, Vertical).svg\n | caption1 = Vertical red flag of the YPG, used since 2011 until early 2013\n\n | image2 = People's Protection Units Flag (2011-2012).svg\n | caption2 = Horizontal red flag of the YPG, used since 2011 until early 2013\n\n | image3 = People's Protection Units Flag (2011-2012) alternative.svg\n | caption3 = Variant of the horizontal red flag, also used until early 2013\n\n | image4 = People's Protection Units Flag.svg\n | caption4 = Yellow flag of the YPG, first used since late 2012, widely adopted in 2013 and since then the official flag of the militia\n}}\n\n=== Units ===\nIn 2017, the YPG began to form units called [[regiment]]s in translation, though they are smaller than comparable units in standard militaries:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Canton\n! style=\"width:5%;\"| Number\n! style=\"width:40%;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Date Established\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Strength\n|-\n| Afrin  || 1 || Martyr Xebat D\u00earik  || 27 Feb 2017 || 236 in 4 battalions\n|-\n| Afrin  || 2 || Martyr Afrin  || 20 April 2017 || 235\n|-\n| Afrin  || 3 || Martyr Rojhilet  || Early June? 2017 || 236\n|-\n| Afrin  || 4 || Martyr Mazloum  || 2 July 2017 || 234\n|-\n| Afrin  || 5 || Martyr Ali\u015f\u00ear  || 27 August 2017 || 303\n|-\n| Afrin  || 7 || Martyr Jayan  || 23 Oct 2017 || 250\n|-\n| Afrin  || 8 || Martyr Bahoz Afrin  || 18 Nov 2017 || 234\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Canton\n! style=\"width:5%;\"| Number\n! style=\"width:40%;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Date Established\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Strength\n|-\n| Kobane || 1 || ?  || 13 Feb 2017 || 80\n|-\n| Kobane  || 2 || Martyr \u015eevger Koban\u00ee Regiment || 18 Feb 2017 || 90\n|-\n| Jazira - al-Hasakah || 1 || Jian Judy and Dogan Fadel  || 20 July 2017 || 500\n|-\n| Jazira - Girk\u00ea Leg\u00ea || 3 || Qere\u00e7ox Martyrs  || 12 July 2017 || 200\n|-\n| Aleppo || 1 || Martyr Shahid Baqour || 30 Sep 2017 || 55 (Martyr Abu Shayar battalion)\n|-\n| Tabqa (SDF) || 1 || Martyr Haboun Arab || 14 Nov 2017 || 250\n|}\n\n=== Tactics ===\nAccording to a report in [[IHS Jane's]] regarding the YPG,\n\n{{quote|Relying on speed, stealth, and surprise, it is the archetypal guerrilla army, able to deploy quickly to front lines and concentrate its forces before quickly redirecting the axis of its attack to outflank and ambush its enemy. The key to its success is autonomy. Although operating under an overarching tactical rubric, YPG brigades are inculcated with a high degree of freedom and can adapt to the changing battlefield.<ref name=\"YPG strategy\">{{cite news |title=Analysis: YPG \u2013 the Islamic State's worst enemy |url=http://www.janes.com/article/43030/analysis-ypg-the-islamic-state-s-worst-enemy}}</ref>}}\n\nThe YPG relies heavily on [[sniper]]s and backs them by suppressing enemy fire using mobile heavy machine guns. It also uses roadside bombs to prevent outflanking maneuvers, particularly at night. Its lines have generally held when attacked by [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) forces who have better equipment, including helmets and body armor.<ref name=\"stephens\">{{cite news| title=Analysis: YPG \u2013 The Islamic State's worst enemy |url=http://www.janes.com/article/43030/analysis-ypg-the-islamic-state-s-worst-enemy |date=11 September 2014|accessdate=13 March 2016 |last=Stephens |first=Michael |newspaper=IHS Jane's 360 }}</ref>\n\nThe YPG and [[People's Defence Forces|People's Defense Forces]] (HPG) have also trained and equipped more than 1,000 [[Yazidis]], who operate in the [[Sinjar Mountains|Mount Sinjar area]] as local defense units under their supervision.<ref name=\"stephens\" />\n\nThe YPG calls itself a people's army, and therefore appoints officers by internal elections.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ahmad|first=Rozh|title=A rare glimpse into Kurdish armed forces in Syrian Kurdistan|work=[[Ekurd.net]]|location=Erbil, Iraq|date=6 August 2012|url=http://www.ekurd.net/mismas/articles/misc2012/8/syriakurd578.htm }}</ref>\n\nA 20-year-old female YPJ fighter named Zlukh Hamo (Nom de guerre: Avesta Khabur) was reported to have carried out a [[suicide attack]] towards Turkish troops and a tank during the early phase of the [[Turkish military operation in Afrin|Afrin Offensive]], killing herself and several soldiers in the process.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/28/world/middleeast/kurds-female-suicide-bomber-syria.html|title=Female Kurdish Fighter Kills Turkish Troops in Likely Suicide Bombing in Syria}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1235721/middle-east|title=Turkish troops targeted in Afrin suicide attack}}</ref> The attack was commended by pro-SDF sources as a courageous attack against a tank using explosives, which killed her in the process.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/280120182|title=Kurdish female fighter detonates herself to destroy a Turkish tank in Afrin, statement}}</ref>\n\n=== Equipment ===\n{{see also|List of military equipment used by Syrian Democratic Forces}}\nCompared to other factions engaged in the Syrian Civil war, the YPG has not received significant foreign assistance in the form of weapons and military equipment. According to the YPG, circumstances led to their capture of less equipment from the Syrian Army than other opposition groups did. The figures are estimates only based on the balance sheet that the YPG regularly publishes of its activities.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018Balance of the War Against Hostile Groups in Rojava, Northern Syria: Year 2015\u2019 |url=http://ypgrojava.com/en/2016/01/01/balance-of-the-war-against-hostile-groups-in-rojava-northern-syria-year-2015/ |accessdate=23 March 2016 |date=23 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126073438/http://ypgrojava.com/en/2016/01/01/balance-of-the-war-against-hostile-groups-in-rojava-northern-syria-year-2015/ |archivedate=26 January 2016 }}</ref>\n\n== International outreach ==\n\n=== Foreign volunteers ===\n{{further|YPG International|International Freedom Battalion}}\n[[File:German, French, and Spanish YPG fighters.png|250px|left|thumb|[[Germans|German]], [[French people|French]], and [[Spanish people|Spanish]] fighters of the YPG in northern Syria.]]\nEx\u2013[[U.S. Army]] soldier [[Jordan Matson]] was among the first foreign volunteers of the YPG. Injured by an ISIL suicide bomb, he developed the \"Lions of Rojava\" recruitment campaign for foreign volunteers,<ref>{{cite web |author=Jennifer Percy |title=Meet the American Vigilantes Who Are Fighting ISIS |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/04/magazine/meet-the-american-vigilantes-who-are-fighting-isis.html |date=30 September 2015 |accessdate=15 December 2015}}</ref> launched on 21 October 2014 on Facebook.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/The-Lions-Of-Rojava/290140627860127|title=The Lions of Rojava|accessdate=15 November 2014|publisher=Facebook}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/islamic-state-ypg-foreign-fighters/26690432.html|title=Kobani Kurds Use Facebook To Recruit Foreign Fighters in Struggle Against IS |date=13 November 2014|accessdate=15 November 2014|publisher=Radio Free Europe Radio Liberty}}</ref> More than 400 volunteers from Europe, the Americas and Australia have joined the YPG {{As of|2015|6|11|lc=y}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/2015/06/more-than-400-fighters-from-australia-america-and-europe-join-ypg|title=SOHR|date=11 June 2015|accessdate=15 November 2015|publisher=Syriahr.com}}</ref> including at least ten U.S. volunteers, three of which were U.S. Army veterans.<ref name=Shah>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/culture/western-comrades-join-kurds-arabs-secularists-yezidis-and-syriac-christians-against-islamic-state_27563|title=Western \"comrades\" join Kurds, Arabs, secularists, Yezidis, and Syriac Christians against Islamic State|date=29 October 2014|accessdate=13 February 2015|publisher=Your Middle East}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/10/06/jordan-matson-joins-kurds-against-islamic-state/16796487/|title=Exclusive: American explains why he's fighting ISIL|date=7 October 2014|accessdate=23 October 2014|publisher=USA Today}}</ref><ref name=bbc23oct>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-29705167|title=The US volunteers who fight with Syria's Kurds|date=23 October 2014|accessdate=23 October 2014|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/article/a-divorced-father-of-two-from-ohio-is-fighting-the-islamic-state-in-syria|title=A Divorced Father-of-Two from Ohio Is Fighting the Islamic State in Syria|date=23 October 2014|accessdate=13 February 2015|publisher=Vice News}}</ref> People from both China and the Chinese diaspora have also joined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-35036879|title=The Chinese man fighting Islamic State with the YPG|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOther prominent foreign volunteers have included [[Brace Belden]], [[Macer Gifford]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/islamic-state/11668576/British-ex-trader-who-fought-Isil-describes-escape-from-Syria.html|title=British ex-trader who fought Isil describes escape from Syria|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en}}</ref> Ryan Lock,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jan/02/briton-ryan-lock-killed-while-fighting-against-isis-in-syria|title=Briton killed while fighting against Isis in Syria|last=Blake|first=Matt|date=2017-01-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Michael Israel,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2016/12/3/foreign-volunteers-fighting-with-syrian-kurdish-forces-killed-by-turkey|title=Foreign volunteers fighting with Syrian-Kurdish forces killed 'by Turkey'|last=Arab|first=The New|work=alaraby|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en}}</ref> Dean Evans,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/oct/29/isis-wasnt-about-killing-people-what-drove-british-farmer-syrian-frontline|title='It wasn't about killing people': what drove a British farmer to the Syrian frontline?|last=Blake|first=Matt|date=2016-10-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-03-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[Jac Holmes]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rudaw.net/english/kurdistan/240420166|title=Three foreign YPG volunteers released from jail, going home |website=rudaw|access-date=2017-03-24}}</ref> [[Anna Campbell]], [[Lorenzo Orsetti]] and [[Haukur Hilmarsson]]. \n\nDozens of non-Kurdish Turks (from both Turkey and the European diaspora) have also joined.<ref name=Shah/> The Turkish [[Marxist-Leninist Communist Party (Turkey)|Marxist-Leninist Communist Party]] (MLKP) has been sending volunteers to fight in the YPG since 2012. At least four have been killed in battle as of February 2015\u2014one during the Battle of Ras al-Ayn and three during the Siege of Koban\u00ee. The party released a video in late January 2015 showing several Spanish- and German-speaking volunteers from Europe among its ranks in [[Jazira Canton]]; they were reorganised into the [[International Freedom Battalion]] on 10 June 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.etha.com.tr/Haber/2015/01/28/guncel/enternasyonal-devrimciler-her-dilden-devrimi-savun/|title=Enternasyonal devrimciler: Her dilden devrimi savunuyoruz|date=28 January 2015|publisher=Etkin Haber Ajans\u0131|language=Turkish|accessdate=11 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302131855/http://www.etha.com.tr/Haber/2015/01/28/guncel/enternasyonal-devrimciler-her-dilden-devrimi-savun/|archive-date=2 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===== Deaths =====\n{{Further information|International_Freedom_Battalion#International_Freedom_Battalion_fatalities}}\nDuring the fight against ISIL and the defense of [[Afrin, Syria|Afrin]] against the Turkish state, several of the international volunteers were wounded and killed. The [[Icelanders|Icelandic]] [[Haukur Hilmarsson]], aged 31, was killed on 24 February 2018 in an [[artillery]] attack by the [[Turkish army]] in the village of [[Maabatli|Mabeta]], Afrin.<ref>https://anfenglish.com/news/internationalists-martyred-in-rojava-remembered-in-greece-33183</ref> As a [[YPJ]] fighter, the British woman [[Anna Campbell]], 26, from [[Lewes]] in [[East Sussex]], was killed in a Turkish airstrike in [[Afrin, Syria|Afrin]] on 15 March 2018.<ref>https://www.rt.com/uk/421667-syria-afrin-ypg-campbell/</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/19/briton-kurds-anna-campbell-dies-fighting-turkey-syria-afrin</ref> In the battle of [[Al-Baghuz Fawqani]], an Italian man fighting for the YPG, [[Lorenzo Orsetti]], was killed on Sunday, 17 March 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-47628209|title=Syrian fighters 'overrun IS encampment'|date=2019-03-19|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\n===== Politics =====\n\nWhile most countries do not object in principle to their citizens joining the ranks of the YPG, Turkey has been vocal against YPG's foreign recruits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/en/originals/2017/06/turkey-syria-kurds-ypg-foreign-militants.html|title=Turkey increasingly vocal against YPG\u2019s foreign recruits|publisher=Al-Monitor|author=Metin Gurcan|date=28 June 2017|access-date=28 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929000711/http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/en/originals/2017/06/turkey-syria-kurds-ypg-foreign-militants.html|archive-date=29 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSeveral Australians, including former [[Australian labour movement|trade unionist]] and politician [[Matthew Gardiner]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/news/northern-territory/matthew-gardiner-confirmed-to-be-fighting-islamic-state-with-kurds/story-fnk0b1zt-1227203073161|title=Matthew Gardiner confirmed to be fighting Islamic State with Kurds|work=NTNews|accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref> have been involved with the YPG despite threats by Australia to prosecute any citizens involved in the Syrian Civil War.<ref name=\"xinhua\">{{cite news |date=11 June 2015 |title=Australian man defends his actions fighting against Islamic State |url=http://english.sina.com/2015/0610/818826.html |agency=[[Xinhua News Agency|Xinhua (Beijing)]] |quote=Former international junior bench press champion Ashley Dyball \u2026 wrote on Facebook, 'The s--- you see here is nothing like you see on the bias news reports, the Islamic state must be stopped and if it means I can\u2019t come home f--- it.' \u2026 Dyball faces prosecution if he returns.}}</ref> Under Australian law it is a criminal offence to fight with any side in a foreign conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lowyinterpreter.org/post/2015/03/25/Awkward-contradictions-in-Australian-foreign-fighter-laws.aspx|title=Awkward contradictions in Australian foreign-fighter laws|author=Lauren Williams|work=lowyinterpreter.org|accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Turkish court sentenced two [[Czech Republic|Czech]] nationals to more than six years in prison for their reported ties to the YPG.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkish Supreme Court upholds six-year verdict imposed on two Czechs |url=https://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/turkish-supreme-court-upholds-six-year-verdict-imposed-on-two-czechs |work=Radio Praha |date=24 July 2018}}</ref> In [[Germany]], the YPG leads to controversies as it is up to the police to begin a prosecution for showing a YPG flag.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peter|first=Erik|url=https://taz.de/!5629632/|title=Kurdische Symbole in Deutschland: Rechtslage? Mal so, mal so|date=2019-10-16|work=Die Tageszeitung: taz|access-date=2020-03-01|language=de|issn=0931-9085}}</ref> In the state of Bavaria, fines for showing a YPG flag are issued, while the federal government declares that the YPG is not forbidden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://anfdeutsch.com/aktuelles/ist-das-zeigen-einer-ypg-fahne-strafbar-7797|title=Ist das Zeigen einer YPG-Fahne strafbar?|website=ANF News|language=de|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>  \n\n=== Foreign government support ===\n{{See also|Syrian Democratic Forces}}\n\nBecause the YPG operates in a landlocked territory, rival opposition groups as well as the Turkish and Syrian government were able to physically prevent foreign aid from reaching it. The YPG's seizure of Til Ko\u00e7er in October 2013 (cf. above) created an overland connection to more or less friendly groups in Iraq, but could not change the even more fundamental problem, that the YPG had no allies willing to provide equipment.\n\n==== United States ====\n[[File:US and YPG officers in northeastern Hasaka.png|thumb|A US military officer and YPG and YPJ commanders tour an area hit by [[April 2017 Turkish airstrikes in Syria and Iraq|Turkish airstrikes]] in April 2017]]\n[[File:YPG and US army Hassaka 1-5-2017.jpg|thumb|U.S. Army [[M1126 Infantry Carrier Vehicle|M1126 Stryker]] armored vehicle in [[Al-Hasakah]], May 2017]]\nIn August 2014 [[Mazlum Kobane|Mazlum Koban\u00ee]] led negotiations with the US in [[Sulaymaniyah|Sulaymaniya]], which led to a military alliance against ISIL.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/dispatch/how-trump-betrayed-the-general-who-defeated-isis|title=How Trump Betrayed the General Who Defeated ISIS|last=Wright|first=Robin|date=2019-04-04|access-date=2019-04-05|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> The United States provided the YPG with air support during the [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-29526783|title=Kobane: Air strikes help Syria town curb IS|date=8 October 2014|accessdate=14 December 2016|via=bbc.com}}</ref> and during later campaigns, helping the YPG defend territory against attacks by the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/dec/01/syria-airstrikes-everything-you-need-to-know|title=Syria airstrikes: everything you need to know|first1=Matthew|last1=Weaver|first2=Julian|last2=Borger|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=14 December 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref> Turkey has criticised US support.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-35541003|title=Turkey's Erdogan denounces US support for Syrian Kurds|date=10 February 2016|accessdate=14 December 2016|via=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe YPG also received 27 bundles totalling 24 tons of small arms and ammunition and 10 tons of medical supplies from the United States and Iraqi Kurdistan during the Siege of Koban\u00ee.<ref name=\"pukmedia\">{{cite web|url=http://pukmedia.com/KS_Direje.aspx?Jimare=69493|title=PUKmedia \u06cc\u06d5\u06a9\u06ce\u062a\u06cc\u06cc \u0646\u06cc\u0634\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u06cc \u06a9\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646|work=pukmedia.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 October 2015, the US began an operation to airdrop 120 tons of military supplies to the YPG and its local Arab and Turkmen allies to fight ISIL north of [[Raqqa]]. The first airdrop consisted of 112 pallets of ammunition and 'other items like hand grenades', totaling 50 tons.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. delivers 50 tons of ammunition to Syria rebel groups |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/10/12/politics/syria-rebel-groups-ammunition-50-tons/index.html|accessdate=1 February 2016|date=12 October 2015}}</ref> However, statements from the US that the aid did not contain TOW's or anti-aircraft weapons made it clear that the U.S. continued to have serious regard for the interests of Turkey, which has warned against continued US support for the YPG. On the other hand, the US also supported Islamist rebel groups who fought the YPG. During the Battle of Aleppo, the US-backed [[Mountain Hawks Brigade]] battled the YPG and the [[Army of Revolutionaries]] for control of the village of [[Maryamin, Afrin|Maryamin]].<ref name=YPGallies>{{cite web |url= http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/ypg-and-allies-clashes-syrian-opposition-groups-aleppo-633986086|title= YPG, allies clash with Syrian opposition groups in Aleppo|date= 29 November 2015|publisher= Middle East Eye}}</ref>\n\nUS aid to the YPG continued in late October with the deployment of up to 50 US special forces to assist the YPG, and an enhanced air campaign to support the YPG and local militia groups in their fight against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]].<ref name=\"steele\">{{cite news |last=Steele |first=Jonathan |title=The Syrian Kurds are winning! |magazine=New York Review of Books |date=3 December 2015 |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/2015/12/03/syrian-kurds-are-winning/ |quote=Turkey had told ... the US that YPG forces would not be permitted to proceed beyond the Euphrates. In an apparent rebuke ... Kerry [said]: \"We\u2019re \u2026 enhancing our air campaign in order to help drive Da\u2019esh, which once dominated the Syria\u2013Turkey border, out of the last seventy-mile stretch...\u201d }} Review of ''Out of Nowhere: The Kurds of Syria in Peace and War'', by Michael M. Gunter.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Obama orders US special forces to 'assist' fight against Isis in Syria \u2019 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/30/syria-us-deployment-troops-obama-special-operations|accessdate=1 February 2016|date=30 October 2015}}</ref> Some of these special forces participated in the [[al-Shaddadi offensive (2016)]] and coordinated airstrikes against ISIL.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aftoBdrjm7Q|title=EXCLUSIVE: Interethnic coalition takes on the IS group in Syria|work=France 24 (Youtube)|date=22 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Battle of Tabqa (2017)]], [[Anti-Terror Units|YPG special forces]] were equipped with US-supplied [[combat helmet]]s, [[AN/PVS-7]] [[night vision device]]s, [[flashlight]]s, and were armed with [[M4 carbine]]s equipped with [[AN/PEQ-2]] [[laser sight]]s, [[holographic weapon sight]]s, and [[STANAG magazine]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.militarytimes.com/articles/syrian-kurds-ypg-us-military-weapons|title=Syrian Kurds are now armed with sensitive US weaponry, and the Pentagon denies supplying it|work=Military Times|author=Shawn Snow|date=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2017, it was announced by the Pentagon that American President [[Donald Trump]] approved of a plan that would have the United States directly provide heavy armaments to the major SDF component group, the YPG; the plan comes before a planned final offensive to capture Raqqa from ISIL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/09/us/politics/trump-kurds-syria-army.html|title=Trump to Arm Syrian Kurds, Even as Turkey Strongly Objects|work=New York Times|date=9 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/05/09/in-blow-to-u-s-turkey-ties-trump-administration-approves-plan-to-directly-arm-syrian-kurds-against-islamic-state/|title=In blow to U.S.-Turkey ties, Trump administration approves plan to arm Syrian Kurds against Islamic State|work=Washington Post|date=9 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/trump-oks-arms-syrian-kurds-turkish-objections-47304210|title=Trump OKs arms for Syrian Kurds, despite Turkish objections|work=ABC News|date=9 May 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509185346/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/trump-oks-arms-syrian-kurds-turkish-objections-47304210|archivedate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nBut there is also a break between American soldiers on the ground and the policy makers in Washington. The soldiers who interact with YPJ-YPG fighters regularly are more fully supportive of their Kurdish allies, and even began wearing patches with the YPG symbol on their American uniforms.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://jacobinmag.com/2018/04/syrian-kurds-rojava-trump-united-states-support|title=The Kurdish Dilemma|last=Hunt|first=Edward|website=jacobinmag.com|access-date=2018-12-05}}</ref> When officials heard of this development, however, the U.S soldiers were ordered to remove the patches. Unlike the soldiers, U.S officials see the YPJ-YPG as \"proxies\"<ref name=\":1\" /> rather than allies.\n\n==== Russia ====\n\nWith Russia's entrance into the war in late 2015 backing the Syrian government, some reports<!-- It is worth noting the source of the reports and their political affiliations in the Syrian Civil War.<ref> --> have reported that the YPG coordinated with or received weapons from Russia, with rival opposition groups stating that the timing and targeting of Russian airstrikes were \"suspiciously advantageous\" to the Kurdish militias.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-mideast-crisis-syria-kurds-idUKKCN0VW16Z|title=Britain says uneasy after evidence of Kurdish coordination with Syria and Russia|website=Reuters UK|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-03-19}}</ref>\n\nDespite this, YPG officials have said they did not cooperate with Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aranews.net/2015/12/kurdish-fighters-in-aleppo-deny-receiving-russian-military-support/|title=Kurdish fighters in Aleppo deny receiving Russian military support \u2013 ARA News|website=ARA News|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328015034/http://aranews.net/2015/12/kurdish-fighters-in-aleppo-deny-receiving-russian-military-support/|archivedate=28 March 2016}}</ref> However in July 2019, [[Rashid Abu Khawla]] the head of the [[Syrian Democratic Forces military councils#Deir ez-Zor|Syrian Democratic Forces' Deir ez-Zor Military Council]] stated that the Syrian Democratic Forces had cooperated with Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://npasyria.com/en/blog.php?id_blog=454&sub_blog=10&name_blog=Abu%20Khawla:%20We%20coordinate%20with%20Russia%20and%20I%20brought%20thousands%20of%20opposition%20fighters%20to%20our%20areas|title=Abu Khawla: We coordinate with Russia and I brought thousands of opposition fighters to our areas|website=npasyria.com}}</ref>\n\n===Diplomatic relations===\n{{See also|Foreign relations of Rojava}}\n\nRussia's position towards the YPG is not clear, and the US actively supports it, but their diplomatic relations with the PYD are the opposite. In January 2016 Russia pushed for the inclusion of the PYD in the Geneva talks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/260120161|title=Russia: Kurds should be included in Geneva talks |website=Rudaw|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref> The YPG would like to open a representative branch in the US, but in March 2016 interview its leader implied that it was not allowed to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kurdistantribune.com/2016/salih-muslim-time-has-proved-us-right/|title=Salih Muslim: Time Has Proved Us Right |website=The Kurdistan Tribune|language=en-US |quote=The West is fully aware that the Syrian Democratic Forces are an important and reliable active on the ground, hence the military support. Unfortunately, they have not yet approached us at a political level while they keep their ties with Saudi Arabia, Turkey ... However, we do hope political relations to materialize among us in the future.|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref>\n\nIn February, 2018, USA's [[Director of National Intelligence]] described YPG as the Syrian wing of PKK in its new report.<ref name=\"DNI2018\">[https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/os-dcoats-021318.PDF Director of National Intelligence, Worldwide threat assessment of the US intelligence community], 13 February 2018. Quote: \"The Kurdish People\u2019s Protection Unit\u2014the Syrian militia of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK)\u2014probably will seek some form of autonomy but will face resistance from Russia, Iran, and Turkey.\"</ref>\n\n=== International media outreach ===\n\nThe YPG's press office media operation has been a particular focus of its opponents, with [[Turkey]] bombing its premises in [[Cizire Canton]] in April 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-39708909|title=Turkey air strikes on Kurds in Syria and Iraq spark US concern|date=25 April 2017|work=BBC}}</ref> and the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) singling out its premises in [[Raqqa]] for a raid during the late stages of the [[Battle of Raqqa (2017)|Battle of Raqqa]] in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/sep/27/british-film-maker-killed-mehmet-aksoy-militants-raqqa-syria|title=British film-maker killed by Isis militants in Syria|date=27 September 2017|work=The Guardian|author=Matt Blake}}</ref>\n\n== Allegations concerning violations of international law and war crimes==\n{{See|\nHuman rights in the Democratic Federation of Northern Syria#DFNS-associated militias|Syrian Democratic Forces#Reported war crimes|Human rights violations during the Syrian Civil War#Syrian Democratic Forces|Human rights in Syria#Human rights in the Democratic Federation of Northern Syria}}\n\n=== Ethnic cleansing ===\n\nIn June 2015 the Turkish government stated that the YPG was carrying out an ethnic cleansing as part of a plan to join the Jazira and [[Koban\u00ee Canton|Koban\u00ee]] cantons into a single territory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Turkey accuses Kurdish forces of 'ethnic cleansing' in Syria|url=https://news.yahoo.com/turkey-accuses-kurdish-forces-ethnic-cleansing-syria-093148734.html|date=16 June 2015|agency=Agence France-Presse|quote=President Recep Tayyip Erdogan on Sunday said he was troubled by the advance of Kurdish forces, saying they could in the future create a structure to threaten Turkey.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]] reacted by starting an inquiry into the allegations.<ref name=\"Rudaw.net\">{{cite web|url=http://rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/14102015?keyword=amnesty|title=US voices concern over allegations of rights violations by YPG|date=14 October 2015|accessdate=20 October 2015 |last1=Saeed |first1=Yerevan |quote=We\u2019ll look closely at all these accusations to determine whether there's any veracity to the claims ... We call on those who actually are or will participate in administering these areas to do so inclusively and with respect for all groups regardless of ethnicity|website=[[Rudaw Media Network|Rudaw]] }}</ref> \n\nIn a report published by the [[United Nations]]' [[Independent International Commission of Inquiry on the Syrian Arab Republic]] on 10 March 2017, the Commission refuted Amnesty International's reports of ethnic cleansing, stating that \"'though allegations of 'ethnic cleansing' continued to be received during the period under review, the Commission found no evidence to substantiate reports that YPG or SDF forces ever targeted Arab communities on the basis of ethnicity.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://komnews.com/syria-and-islamist-groups-guilty-of-war-crimes-ypg-cleared-un-report/|title=Syria and Islamist groups guilty of war crimes, YPG cleared: UN report|work=Kom News|date=15 March 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317054645/https://komnews.com/syria-and-islamist-groups-guilty-of-war-crimes-ypg-cleared-un-report/|archivedate=17 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"UN report counters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/un-report-counters-amnesty-internationals-claim-that-kurds-are-ethnically-cleansing-in-syria/|title=UN report counters Amnesty International's claim that Kurds are ethnically cleansing in Syria|first=Paul|last=Antonopoulos|date=15 March 2017|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"refutes\">{{cite web|url=http://ekurd.net/ypg-changing-demographics-2017-03-14|title=UN report refutes ethnic cleansing claims against Syrian Kurdish YPG, SDF|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Forced displacement ===\n\nIn October 2015, [[Amnesty International]] published a report<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=In July and August 2015 Amnesty International investigated the forced displacement of residents from 10 villages and towns in areas under the control of the Autonomous Administration}}</ref> with reports that the YPG had driven at least 100 families from northern Syria and that in the villages of Asaylem and Husseiniya it had demolished resident homes. The report was made by Amnesty visiting the area contained in the report. It made local observations of destruction, and collected testimonies from former and actual residents of [[Al-Hasakah Governorate|al-Hasakeh]] and [[Raqqa Governorate|Raqqa]] governorates. It found cases of YPG fighters forcibly displacing residents and using fire and bulldozers to raze homes and other structures.<ref name=\"amnesty.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2015/10/syria-us-allys-razing-of-villages-amounts-to-war-crimes|title=Syria: US ally\u2019s razing of villages amounts to war crimes|work=Amnesty International|date=13 October 2015|accessdate=17 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite news |date=13 October 2015 |title=Syria Kurds 'razing villages seized from IS' \u2013 Amnesty |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-34511134|agency=[[BBC News]] |quote=Of 225 buildings visible [in Husseiniya] in June 2014, only 14 were still standing by June 2015. }}</ref>\n\nForced displacement of civilians and destruction of civilian property is not a war crime per se. These acts only become a war crime when there is no \"imperative military necessity\" for them. Amnesty International stated the report documents cases in which there was no such justification.<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=this report documents cases in which there was no such justification}}</ref> It furthermore states that \"the circumstances of some of these displacements suggested that they were carried out in retaliation for people's perceived sympathies with, or family ties to, suspected members of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] or other armed groups\",<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=The circumstances of some of the instances of forced displacement documented in this report suggest that they were carried out in retaliation for people's perceived sympathies with, or family ties to, suspected members of IS or other armed groups. This would constitute collective punishment, which is a violation of international humanitarian law.}}</ref> thus constituting \"collective punishment, which is a violation of international humanitarian law\".\n\nIn interviews, YPG spokespersons acknowledged that a number of families were in fact displaced. However, they placed the number at no more than 25,<ref>{{Citation|last=Amnesty International|title=\"We had nowhere else to go\": Forced displacement and demolitions in northern Syria|date=2015-10-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LlOzoCHaNeM&t=2m10s|accessdate=2016-03-19}}</ref> and stated military necessity. They stated that the family members of terrorists maintained communications with them, and therefore had to be removed from areas where they might pose a danger.<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=In some dangerous areas there are some specific cases that are very small, resulting from the terrorist threat, where families were sent away from the area ... Only 25 families were forced to leave across Rojava ... (They are told) 'Folks, remove your things please, and if you leave from this area until the war ends it will be a good thing ...' You have terrorists in al-Raqqa and their families \u2013 the uncle, and brother, and sister \u2013 are here, and they are in communication, giving them information. We were forced to distance these families. Not detain them. Distance them. Take them outside of the area.}}</ref> They further stated that ISIL was using civilians in those areas to plant car bombs or carry out other attacks on the YPG.<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=He added that IS was benefiting from the presence of civilians in these areas, and using them to plant car bombs or carry out other attacks on the YPG.}}</ref> By describing the events in Hammam al-Turkman before the village was evacuated, the Amnesty International report itself inadvertently supports these YPG reports of military necessity.<ref>{{cite web|title=We had nowhere else to go, Forced displacement and demolition in northern Syria|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/MDE2425032015ENGLISH.PDF|date=October 2015|quote=After the YPG took the village, on 15 June, a car bomb killed three YPG fighters 4&nbsp;km from Hammam al-Turkman at a checkpoint in Damishli. The following day there were skirmishes between the YPG and IS in the village before IS was pushed back. A second car bomb went off at a YPG checkpoint at the health clinic in the village on 18 June killing a YPG fighter and injuring one civilian and three days later IS shot and killed a second YPG fighter near the clinic. It was after the death of this fighter that the residents were told by the YPG that they had to leave the village.}}</ref>\n\n=== Recruitment of minors ===\n\nIn June 2014, [[Human Rights Watch]] criticized the YPG for accepting minors into their ranks,<ref name=\"hrw\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/en/world-report-2009/china |title=World Report 2009: China|publisher=Human Rights Watch |accessdate=14 July 2009}}</ref> picking up on multiple earlier reports of teenage fighters serving in the YPG, with a report by the [[United Nations]] [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary General]] stating that 24 minors under age of 18 had been recruited by YPG, with 124 having been recruited by the Free Syrian Army and 5 by the Syrian Arab Army.<ref name=\"children\">{{cite report |author=[[United Nations Security Council|U.N. Security Council]] |date=5 June 2015 |title=Report of the Secretary-General: Children and armed conflict |url=https://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A/69/926 |at=para. 191 |quote=Actual numbers are expected to be higher.... A number of pro-Government groups, including Hizbullah, also reportedly recruited children in small numbers.}}</ref> In response, the YPG and YPJ signed the [[Geneva Call]] ''Deed of Commitment'' protecting children in armed conflict, prohibiting sexual violence and against gender discrimination in July 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/syrian-arab-republic/syria-4-brigades-free-syrian-army-commit-prohibit-sexual-violence-and|title=Syria: 4 brigades of the Free Syrian Army commit to prohibit sexual violence and the use of child soldiers [EN/AR] - Syrian Arab Republic}}</ref> and Kurdish security forces (YPG and [[Asayish (Syria)|Asayish]]) began receiving human rights training from [[Geneva Call]] and other international organisations with the YPG pledging publicly to demobilize all fighters under 18 within a month and began to enact disciplinary measures against commanders of the units that had involved in corruption and accepting recruit under age of 18 to their ranks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Syria: Kurdish Forces Violating Child Soldier Ban Despite Promises, Children Still Fight|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/07/10/syria-kurdish-forces-violating-child-soldier-ban-0|website=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Perry |first1=Tom |last2=Malla |first2=Naline |date=10 September 2015 |title=Western states train Kurdish force in Syria, force's leader says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/09/10/uk-mideast-crisis-syria-kurds-idUKKCN0RA1MO20150910 |agency=[[Reuters]] |quote=Amnesty International this month faulted the Kurdish administration for arbitrary detentions and unfair trials.... [Ciwan] Ibrahim said ... efforts were underway to improve its human rights record.... The Geneva Call ... promotes good treatment of civilians in war zones... }}</ref> In October 2015 the YPG demobilized 21 minors from the military service in its ranks.<ref name=\"Demobilized children\">{{cite report |date=28 October 2015 |title=YPG demobilizes 21 children under the age of 18 from the military service in its ranks |url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/2015/10/ypg-demobilizes-21-children-under-the-age-of-18-from-the-military-service-in-its-ranks/ |publisher=[[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121223140/http://supportkurds.org/news/wednesday-28-october-2015/ |archivedate=2015-11-21 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Human Rights Watch<ref>{{cite web|title=Syria: Armed Group Recruiting Children in Camps|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2018/08/03/syria-armed-group-recruiting-children-camps|website=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> and the annual UN report of 2018,<ref>{{cite report |url=http://undocs.org/s/2018/465|author=[[United Nations Security Council|U.N. Security Council]] |date=16 May 2018 |title=Report of the Secretary-General: Children and armed conflict |access-date=23 October 2019 }}</ref> there were 224 cases of child recruitment by the YPG and its women's unit, the YPJ, in 2017, an almost fivefold increase from the previous year.  This sparked immediate conversations with the anti-child-recruitment [[NGO]] [[Geneva Call]] which resulted in a broad new military directive strictly prohibiting all recruitment of persons under 18, ordering that any such persons within SDF be immediately removed from the payroll and transferred to the custody of the civilian Authority For Education, mandating the appointment of an [[ombudsman]] in each military service to receive and investigate reports of child recruitment, and ordering punitive measures by military police and by the SDF's Military Discipline Department against anyone found to be responsible for child recruitment. [[Geneva Call]] immediately praised the SDF's wide-ranging initiative to eliminate and prevent child recruitment throughout all of SDF's military organizations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/380c0f07-bd15-4d0b-b57b-1cd23b7bf977 |title=SDF command issues order banning child recruitment |date=7 September 2018  |access-date=23 October 2019 |publisher=Kurdistan24 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Asia|War}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[International Freedom Battalion]]\n* [[Jabhat al-Akrad]]\n* [[Kurdistan Workers' Party]] (PKK)\n* [[Party of Free Life of Kurdistan]] (PJAK)\n* [[Peshmerga]]\n* [[Siege of Koban\u00ee]]\n* [[Sutoro]]\n* [[YPG\u2013FSA relations]]\n* [[YPG\u2013Syrian government conflict]]\n* [[List of armed groups in the Syrian Civil War]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book\n|last=Rashid\n|first=Bedir Mulla\n|translator=Obaida Hitto\n|title= Military and Security Structures of the Autonomous Administration in Syria\n|url=http://omranstudies.org/publications/reports/download/68_d403f01ed28320cb2e67b13cffb381c7.html\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701140230/http://omranstudies.org/publications/reports/download/68_d403f01ed28320cb2e67b13cffb381c7.html\n|url-status=dead\n|archive-date=2018-07-01\n|orig-year=1st pub. 2017\n|date= 2018\n|publisher= Omran for Strategic Studies\n|location= [[Istanbul]]\n|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Facebook|RojavaDefenseUnits|name=People's Defense Units YPG}}\n{{Syrian Kurdistan topics}}\n{{Kurdish nationalist organisations}}\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n\n[[Category:Apoist organizations in Syria]]\n[[Category:People's Protection Units| ]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in Syria]]\n[[Category:Kurdistan Communities Union]]\n[[Category:Syrian Kurdish organizations]]\n[[Category:Irregular units and formations]]\n[[Category:Democratic Federation of Northern Syria]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2011]]\n", "name_user": "Australian Coin Information", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:Added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/People%27s_Protection_Units"}
{"title_page": "William Cullen", "text_new": "{{other people|William Cullen}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = William Cullen\n|image             = William Cullen.jpg\n|image_size        =\n|caption           = William Cullen\n|birth_date        = 15 April 1710\n|birth_place       = [[Hamilton, Scotland|Hamilton]], [[Lanarkshire]], [[Scotland]]<ref>Thomson, John. [https://books.google.com/books?id=F0EBAAAAQAAJ&dq=William%20Cullen%20John%20Thomson&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false ''An Account of the Life, Lectures and Writings of William Cullen, M.D. Volume 1'']. William Blackwood & T. Cadell, 1832, p. 1.</ref>\n|death_date        = {{d-da|5 February 1790|15 April 1710}}\n|death_place       = [[Edinburgh, Scotland|Edinburgh]], Scotland<ref>Thomson, John; Thomson, William; Craigie, David. [https://books.google.com/books?id=9SwAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA660#v=onepage&q&f=false ''An Account of the Life, Lectures and Writings of William Cullen, M.D. Volume 2'']. William Blackwood & Sons, 1859, p. 660.</ref>\n|residence         =\n|citizenship       =\n|nationality       = Scottish\n|alma_mater        = [[University of Glasgow]] <br /> [[University of Edinburgh]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|notable_students  = [[Joseph Black]], [[Benjamin Rush]], [[John Walker (natural historian)|John Walker]], [[John Morgan (physician)|John Morgan]], [[George Fordyce]], [[William Withering]], [[John Haygarth]], [[John Moore (Scottish physician)|John Moore]], [[John Brown (doctor)|John Brown]], [[Robert Willan]], [[Sir Gilbert Blane]], [[John Coakley Lettsom]]\n|known_for         = Teaching at the [[Edinburgh Medical School]], author of popular medical textbook ''First Lines of the Practice of Physic'', [[Scottish Enlightenment]] figure and mentor to [[Joseph Black]]\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        =\n|influenced        =\n|signature         =\n|footnotes         =\n|ethnicity         =\n|field             = Medicine, [[Chemistry]], Agriculture\n|work_institutions =\n|prizes            =\n|religion          =\n}}\n[[File:Cameo of William Cullen (close-up), Hunterian Museum, Glasgow.jpg|thumb|Cameo of William Cullen (close-up), Hunterian Museum, Glasgow]]\n[[File:Cullen William.jpg|thumb|William Cullen]]\n[[File:Burial enclosure of William and Robert Cullen - geograph.org.uk - 1050342.jpg|thumb|Burial enclosure of William and Robert Cullen in Kirknewton]]\n'''William Cullen''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] [[FRSE]] [[FRCPE]] [[FPSG]] ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u028c|l|\u0259n}}; 15 April 1710&nbsp;\u2013 5 February 1790) was a Scottish physician, chemist and agriculturalist, and one of the most important professors at the [[Edinburgh Medical School]], during its heyday as the leading centre of medical education in the English-speaking world.<ref>Thomson, John. [https://books.google.com/books?id=F0EBAAAAQAAJ&dq=William%20Cullen%20John%20Thomson&pg=PR3#v=onepage&q&f=false ''An Account of the Life, Lectures and Writings of William Cullen, M.D. Volume 1'']. William Blackwood & T. Cadell, 1832.</ref>\n\nCullen was also a central figure in the [[Scottish Enlightenment]]. He was [[David Hume]]'s physician and friend, and on intimate terms with [[Adam Smith]], [[Lord Kames]] (with whom he discussed theoretical and practical aspects of husbandry), [[Joseph Black]], [[John Millar (philosopher)|John Millar]], and [[Adam Ferguson]], among others.\n\nHe was President of the Royal College of Physicians and Surgeons of Glasgow (1746\u201347), President of the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]] (1773\u20131775) and First Physician to the King in Scotland (1773\u20131790).<ref>Doig, A., Ferguson, J. P. S., Milne, I. A., and Passmore, R. ''William Cullen and the Eighteenth Century Medical World''. Edinburgh University Press, 1993, pp. xii\u2013xiii.</ref> He was also, incidentally, one of the prime movers in obtaining a [[royal charter]] for the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh, resulting in the formation of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] in 1783.<ref name=\"Waterston\">{{cite book\n |last1       = Waterston\n |first1      = Charles D\n |last2       = Macmillan Shearer\n |first2      = A\n |title       = Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783\u20132002: Biographical Index\n |url         = http://www.rse.org.uk/fellowship/fells_indexp1.pdf\n |accessdate  = 29 September 2010\n |volume      = I\n |date        = July 2006\n |publisher   = [[The Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n |location    = Edinburgh\n |isbn        = 978-0-902198-84-5\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061004113545/http://www.rse.org.uk/fellowship/fells_indexp1.pdf\n |archivedate = 4 October 2006\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nCullen was a beloved teacher, and many of his students became influential figures in their own right. His best-known students\u2014many of whom continued to correspond with him during his long life\u2014included (in addition to [[Joseph Black]], who became his colleague) [[Benjamin Rush]], a central figure in the founding of the United States of America; [[John Morgan (physician)|John Morgan]], who founded the first medical school in the American colonies (the Medical School at the [[College of Philadelphia]]);<ref>{{Cite journal|jstor = 3143563|title = Some American Students of \"That Shining Oracle of Physic,\" Dr. William Cullen of Edinburgh, 1755-1766|journal = Proceedings of the American Philosophical Society|volume = 94|issue = 3|pages = 275\u2013281|last1 = Bell|first1 = Whitfield J|year = 1950}}</ref> [[William Withering]], the discoverer of [[digitalis]]; [[Sir Gilbert Blane]], medical reformer of the [[Royal Navy]]; and [[John Coakley Lettsom]], the philanthropist and founder of the [[Medical Society of London]].<ref>Doig, A., Ferguson, J. P. S., Milne, I. A., and Passmore, R. ''William Cullen and the Eighteenth Century Medical World''. Edinburgh University Press, 1993, esp. pp. 40\u201355.</ref>\n\nSpecial mention must be made of Cullen's student-turned-opponent, [[John Brown (doctor)|John Brown]], who developed the medical system known as [[Brunonian system of medicine|Brunonianism]], which rivalled Cullen's. This was to have immense influence, especially in Italy and Germany, during the end of the eighteenth and beginning of the nineteenth century.<ref>Bynum, W.F. and Porter, Roy. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/issues/172551/ ''Brunonianism in Britain and Europe'']. ''Medical History'', Supplement No. 8 (1988), pp. ix\u2013x.</ref>\n\nCullen was also a successful author. He published a number of medical textbooks, mostly for the use of his students, though they were popular throughout Europe and the American colonies as well. His best known work was ''First Lines of the Practice of Physic'', which was published in a series of editions between 1777 and 1784.<ref>Doig, A., Ferguson, J. P. S., Milne, I. A., and Passmore, R. ''William Cullen and the Eighteenth Century Medical World''. Edinburgh University Press, 1993, esp. pp. 34\u201339.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCullen was born in [[Hamilton, Scotland|Hamilton]], Lanarkshire.<ref name=\"royalsoced.org.uk\">https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp1.pdf</ref> His father William was a lawyer retained by the [[Duke of Hamilton]] as [[Factor (Scotland)|factor]], and his mother was Elizabeth Roberton of Whistlebury.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nahste.ac.uk/isaar/GB_0237_NAHSTE_P0251.html |title=Cullen &#124; William &#124; 1710\u20131790 &#124; physician, chemist and metallurgist |publisher=Nahste.ac.uk |accessdate=20 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204201758/http://www.nahste.ac.uk/isaar/GB_0237_NAHSTE_P0251.html |archivedate=4 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.familysearch.org/eng/search/frameset_search.asp |title=Free Family History and Genealogy Records \u2013 |publisher=Familysearch.org |date= |accessdate=22 April 2013}}</ref> He studied at the Old Grammar School of Hamilton (renamed in 1848 The [[Hamilton Academy]]), then, in 1726, began a General Studies arts course at the [[University of Glasgow]]. He began his medical training as apprentice to John Paisley, a [[Glasgow]] apothecary surgeon, then spent 1729 as surgeon on a merchant vessel trading between London and the [[West Indies]]. After two years as assistant apothecary to Mr Murray of Henrietta Street, London, he returned to Scotland in 1732 to establish himself in general medical practice in the parish of [[Shotts]], Lanarkshire. From 1734 to 1736 he studied medicine at the [[University of Edinburgh]], where he became interested in chemistry, and was one of the founders of the [[Royal Medical Society]] in his first year of study.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cullenproject.ac.uk/about/|title=About the Cullen Project|last=|first=|date=|website=The Cullen Project|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1736 he began medical practice in Hamilton, where he rapidly acquired a high reputation. He also continued his study of the [[natural science]]s, especially of [[chemistry]]. From 1737 to 1740 [[William Hunter (anatomist)|William Hunter]] was his resident pupil, and at one time they proposed to enter into partnership. In 1740 Cullen was awarded the degree of MD from [[Glasgow University]]. In 1741, he married and started his family. He became ordinary medical attendant to James Douglas, 5th [[Duke of Hamilton]] (1703\u201343), his family, and his livestock. In 1744, following the Duke's death, the Cullens moved to [[Glasgow]].\n\nIn Glasgow he gave extramural lectures for the University, on physiology, botany, materia medica, and chemistry. His great abilities, enthusiasm, and use of practical demonstrations for instruction, made him a successful and highly popular teacher, attracting large classes. At the same time he also maintained a medical practice. In 1747, Cullen was awarded Britain's first independent lectureship in Chemistry and was elected President of the Faculty of Physicians and Surgeons of Glasgow. In 1748 while in Glasgow, Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although is not credited with a usable application. In 1751 he was appointed [[Regius Professor of Medicine and Therapeutics, Glasgow|Professor of the Practice of Medicine]], although he continued to lecture on chemistry.\n\n==Edinburgh==\nIn 1755 he was enticed by [[Lord Kames]] to become Professor of Chemistry and Medicine at the [[University of Edinburgh]]. It was in Edinburgh, in 1756, that he gave the first documented public demonstration of artificial [[refrigeration]].<ref>William Cullen, ''Of the Cold Produced by Evaporating Fluids and of Some Other Means of Producing Cold,'' '''in''' Essays and Observations Physical and Literary Read Before a Society in Edinburgh and Published by Them, II, (Edinburgh 1756)</ref> Cullen used a pump to create a partial [[vacuum]] over a container of [[diethyl ether]], which then [[boiling point|boiled]], absorbing [[Heat of vaporization|heat]] from the surroundings. This created a small amount of ice, but the process found no commercial application.\n\nFrom 1757 he delivered lectures on [[clinical medicine]] in the [[Edinburgh Royal Infirmary]]. On the death of [[Charles Alston (professor)|Charles Alston]] in 1760, Cullen at the request of the students undertook to finish his course of lectures on ''materia medica''; he delivered an entirely new course, notes of which were published in an unauthorised edition in 1771, but which he re-wrote and issued as ''A Treatise on Materia Medica'' in 1789.\n\nOn the death of [[Robert Whytt]], the professor of the institutes of medicine, Cullen accepted the chair, at the same time resigning that of chemistry. In the same year, he had been an unsuccessful candidate for the professorship of the practice of physic (medicine), but subsequently an arrangement was made between him and [[John Gregory (moralist)|John Gregory]], the successful candidate, by which they both agreed to deliver alternate courses on the theory and practice of medicine. This arrangement continued until the sudden death of Gregory in 1773. Cullen was then appointed sole professor of the practice of physic, and he continued in this office until a few months before his death.\n\nIn 1783 Cullen (together with his sons) was a co-founder of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]].<ref name=\"royalsoced.org.uk\"/>\n\nHe died on 5 February 1790 at his home Ormiston Hill<ref>Williamson's Street Directory 1784</ref> in [[Kirknewton, West Lothian]], and is buried in the churchyard there. His son [[Robert Cullen, Lord Cullen|Robert]] lies with him.\n\n==Influence==\n\nCullen taught many students who would go on to influential careers in British science.  Indeed, a large number of the doctors who taught in Edinburgh's medical school from the 1790s to 1810s had studied with him, including the chemist Joseph Black, the anatomist Alexander Monro Secundus, and the naturalist [[John Walker (natural historian)|John Walker]]. Cullen's emphasis on the practical benefits of chemistry made his ideas popular amongst farmers, industrialists, naturalists and doctors alike.  His influence on these fields was felt through the writings of his students, particularly in the books of John Anderson, the 'Aberdeen Agricola',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Eddy|first1=Matthew Daniel|title='The Aberdeen Agricola: Chemical Principles and Practice in James Anderson's Georgics and Geology |journal=In Lawrence Principe (Ed.), New Narratives in Eighteenth-Century Chemistry|volume=18|date=Springer: 2007|pages=139\u2013156|url=https://www.academia.edu/3667295|doi=10.1007/978-1-4020-6278-0_7|isbn=978-1-4020-6273-5|series=Archimedes}}</ref> and the lectures given by Joseph Black and John Walker from the 1770s to 1790s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Eddy|first1=Matthew Daniel|title=The Language of Mineralogy: John Walker, Chemistry and the Edinburgh Medical School 1750\u20131800|date=2008|publisher=Ashgate|url=https://www.academia.edu/1112014}}</ref>\n\nBy studying the symptoms of diseases, Cullen classified diseases into different classes. One class of diseases was called \"neuroses.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Science and the Practice of Medicine in the Nineteenth Century|last=Bynum|first=William|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1994|isbn=978-0-521-27205-6|location=Cambridge|pages=15\u201316|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Medical practice ==\nIn the 18th century, there were three primary professions in medicine: physicians, surgeons, and apothecaries, although the barriers among them were starting to become blurred. William Cullen practiced as all three.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=William Cullen and the eighteenth century medical world : a bicentenary exhibition and symposium arranged by the Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh in 1990|last=Milne|first=I.|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|year=1993|isbn=978-0-7486-0302-2|location=Edinburgh|pages=110\u2013160}}</ref> Because medical practitioners were not as established as they are now, patients generally took advice from a myriad of sources, including personal experience, books, and several consultations. Furthermore, because the diagnostic tools were not as advanced, patient history was the primary and most important information for the physicians to diagnose their patients.<ref name=\":0\" /> There were no strict government regulations in place for physicians, surgeons, and apothecaries.<ref name=\":0\" /> As a result, to become successful in the medical marketplace depended more on social skills than on medical expertise, similar to other forms of businesses.<ref name=\":0\" /> Cullen was one of the more successful physicians because of his shrewdness in handling difficult patients.<ref name=\":0\" /> Teaching at the University and seeing patients at the Edinburgh Infirmary as charity also helped Cullen become more famous.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMany of Cullen's consultations were done through written letters sent by patients from Scottish cities and towns.<ref name=\":0\" /> Cullen managed his consultations with great efficiency; he usually read the letters early in the morning and his secretary-amanuensis would record and mail back his responses.<ref name=\":0\" /> He then went around Edinburgh to visit patients. This form of epistolary consultations was often limited by the literacy and socioeconomic status of the patients. Patients who would write letters to Cullen were usually in the upper and middle class. Besides letters from patients, he also consulted physicians, often students he had taught.<ref name=\":0\" /> Based on how his letters were written, Cullen was most likely a \"tactful and compassionate practitioner.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Like many physicians in his time, Cullen would often prescribe therapeutics \"to support the patient's endangered constitution and assist the body's natural healing tendencies.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> This is because medical practitioners at the time mostly believed that diseases and illnesses were unique to different patients depending on their constitutions.\n\n== Medical teaching ==\nAccording to Rocca, Cullen was known for systemizing and promoting medical knowledge rather than producing original research.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Brain, Mind and Medicine: Essays in Eighteenth-Century Neuroscience - Springer|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-0-387-70967-3|year = 2007|isbn = 978-0-387-70966-6|last1 = Whitaker|first1 = Harry|last2=Smith|first2=C.U.M|last3=Finger|first3=Stanley}}</ref> Despite the lack of original work, some believed that Cullen's attempt to organize existing knowledge was actually a sign of his \"practical sagacity\" as a practitioner.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|title=William Cullen and the eighteenth century medical world : a bicentenary exhibition and symposium arranged by the Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh in 1990|last=Milne|first=I.|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|year=1993|isbn=978-0-7486-0302-2|location=Edinburgh|pages=110\u2013160}}</ref> He was a lecturer for more than forty years.<ref name=\":02\" /> In order to understand Cullen's medical teaching at the time, it is important to understand Cullen's conception of \"system\" as he taught it in his classes. Cullen described a system as \"an organised body of opinions on particular topics in the medical curriculum.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> He also referred to system as the principles in his book ''First Lines of the Practice of Physic.''<ref name=\":02\" /> There were many possible reasons behind Cullen's emphasis of the system of medicine. In the 18th century, a period of Scottish Enlightenment, there were competing theories about the mechanisms of the human body and the causes of diseases proposed by different professors, who competed for students' teaching fees.<ref name=\":02\" /> Thus, having an underlying system of medical knowledge was a practical way to organize the knowledge coherently for the students.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nLike many prominent medical figures in the 18th century, William Cullen took a great interest in the nervous system. He defined the nervous system as an \"animated machine\" whose main function is to \"perform a variety of motions,\" communicate and interact with \"external bodies.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Cullen believed that the nervous system was composed of four elements: the medullary substance, consisting of the brain and the spinal cord, the membranous nerves, the sensory nerves, and the muscular fibers.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nCullen's understanding of the nervous system was also influenced by his contemporaries, one of whom was [[Albrecht von Haller]] (1708\u20131777).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eds.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?sid=fe84e265-d9e0-4c7c-a22d-8983fc63ab0a@sessionmgr4010&vid=0&hid=4213&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZSZzY29wZT1zaXRl#AN=101560475&db=hia|title=Cullen, a Cautionary Tale: EBSCOhost|website=eds.a.ebscohost.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref> Haller proposed that tissues, including muscles, were characterized by \"irritability\" (or contractility), while nerves were characterized by \"sensibility\" (or feeling).<ref name=\":1\" /> Using Haller's characterization, Cullen defined disease \"as an excess or deficiency of sensibility.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> However, Cullen interpreted sensibility as \"muscle mobility and vigour\" and diseases were caused by the imbalance of irritability and sensibility.<ref name=\":1\" /> Based on this definition of disease, his therapeutics \"either stimulated or sedated the nervous system.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> He categorized diseases into four main classes: pyrexiae, neuroses, cachexiae, and locales. Within the classes were nineteen orders and 132 genera.<ref name=\":1\" /> The four orders of neuroses were comata, adynamiae, spasmi and vesaniae.<ref name=\":1\" /> Comata was defined as \"a diminution of voluntary motion, with sleep, or a deprivation of the senses.\" Adynamiae is defined as \"a diminution of the involuntary motions, whether vital or natural.\" Spasmi was defined as \"irregular motions of the muscles or muscular fibers.\" Vesaniae was defined as \"disorders of the judgement without any pyrexia or coma.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nCullen's emphasis on the importance of the nervous system was driven by the understanding that the nervous system controls the human body and therefore, \"all diseases may, in some sense, be called affections of the nervous system, because, in almost every disease, the nerves are more or less hurt.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Although Cullen's nosology did not last very long, Cullen's influential teachings on medical knowledge and his attempt to systematize and generalize medical knowledge were integral parts of 18th century Scottish Enlightenment.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Family==\n\nIn 1741 he married Anne (or Anna) Johnstone (d.1786).\n\nHe was father to the judge [[Robert Cullen, Lord Cullen]] and to the physician [[Henry Cullen]]. Cullen's eldest son Robert became a Scottish judge in 1796 under the title of Lord Cullen later Baron Cullen,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/portrait.asp?search=as&grp=1095%3BScottish+sitters+and+artists&lDate=&LinkID=mp55787&rNo=0&role=sit |title=NPG D2239; Robert Cullen, Baron Cullen |publisher=Npg.org.uk |date= |accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref> and was known for his powers of [[impressionist (entertainment)|mimicry]].\n\n==Publications==\nBecause of the wide popularity of Cullen's work, many of his publications were translated into a multitude of languages across Europe.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Science and the Practice of Medicine in the Nineteenth Century|last=Bynum|first=W.F.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1994|isbn=978-0-521-27205-6|location=New York|pages=11|quote=|via=}}</ref> Cullen's most popular and successful work was his medical textbook ''First Lines of the Practice of Physic'', published in two volumes in 1777 and expanded with each edition until it reached four volumes in its final edition (1784).\n\nHis first book-length publication was ''Synopsis Nosologiae Methodicae'' (1769), Cullen's very influential nosology, or classification of diseases. His next publication was also a medical textbook, and it dealt with the Institutions of medicine, i.e. medical theory. Its full title was ''Institutions of Medicine. Part I. Physiology'' (1772) because it focused on physiology, which was traditionally only one part of the Institutions (pathology and therapeutics were also essential parts of medical theory). It went through two more editions (1777 & 1785).\n\nWork on his magnum opus, ''First Lines of Practice of Physic'', occupied much of his time in the 1770s and 1780s, but he did manage one final publication. This was his two volume ''A Treatise of the Materia Medica'' (1789), which was highly valued by other medical practitioners throughout Europe.\n\nThus, the following works, with their dates of publication (including multiple editions), comprise the majority of Cullen's ''oevre'':\n\n*''Synopsis Nosologiae Methodicae'' (1769; 1771; 1780; 1785)\n* ''Lectures on the Materia medica''. 2nd Ed. Dublin : Whitestone, 1781. [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:061:2-169327 Digital edition] of the [[University and State Library D\u00fcsseldorf]].\n* ''Cours de Mati\u00e8re m\u00e9dicale.'' Paris, 1788. [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:061:2-148946 Digital edition] of the [[University and State Library D\u00fcsseldorf]].\n*''Institutions of Medicine. Part I. Physiology'' (1772; 1777; 1785)\n*''First Lines of the Practice of Physic'' (1777; 1778; 1781; 1784; 1793 ([http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t1zc7sg8v vol.&nbsp;1]; [http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t4hm53f54?urlappend=%3Bseq=5 vol.&nbsp;2]))\n*''A Treatise of the Materia Medica'' (1789)\n** ''Trait\u00e9 de Mati\u00e8re m\u00e9dicale'' translated by \u00c9douard Fran\u00e7ois Marie Bosquillon. Published: vol. 1 \u2013 3. Pavie : Sauveur, 1791. [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:061:2-148969 Digital edition] of the [[University and State Library D\u00fcsseldorf]].\n** ''Trattato di Materia medica''. Involved: Dalladecima, Angelo. 2. Ed. Erschienen: Bd. 1 \u2013 6. Padova : Bettinelli, 1798. [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:061:2-148955 Digital edition] of the [[University and State Library D\u00fcsseldorf]].\n\nCullen also published a few, shorter works (e.g. \"A Letter to Lord Cathcart\" in 1776), which have not been included in this list.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Cullen, William|volume=7|pages=616\u2013617}}\n\n=== Basic biographical sources ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Thomson, John. [https://books.google.com/books?id=F0EBAAAAQAAJ&dq=William%20Cullen%20John%20Thomson&pg=PR3#v=onepage&q&f=false ''An Account of the Life, Lectures and Writings of William Cullen, M.D. Volume 1'']. William Blackwood & T. Cadell, 1832.\n*Thomson, John; Thomson, William; [[David Craigie|Craigie, David]]. [https://books.google.com/books?id=9SwAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR1 ''An Account of the Life, Lectures and Writings of William Cullen, M.D. Volume 2'']. William Blackwood & Sons, 1859. This book, in conjunction with its predecessor (see previous reference), is the standard biography of William Cullen's life and thought.\n*Doig, A., Ferguson, J. P. S., Milne, I. A., and Passmore, R (Editors). ''William Cullen and the Eighteenth Century Medical World''. Edinburgh University Press, 1993. This collection of edited essays is the most recent, full-length work on the life and thought of William Cullen. It was the result of an exhibition and symposium at the Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh in 1990 to commemorate the bicentenary of Cullen's death.\n*Bynum, W. F.. \"William Cullen (1710\u20131790).\" ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''. Oxford University Press, 2004. http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/6874.\n* Eddy, M. D. 'Dr. William Cullen, M.D., (1710\u20131790)', ''New Dictionary of Scientific Biography'', Noretta Koertge (ed.), (New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 2007).\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== William Cullen and chemistry ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Donovan, Arthur L. ''Philosophical Chemistry in the Scottish Enlightenment: The Doctrines and Discoveries of William Cullen and Joseph Black''. Edinburgh: University Press, 1975.\n*J V Golinski, \"Utility and Audience in Eighteenth-Century Chemistry: Case Studies of William Cullen and Joseph Priestley,\" ''The British Journal for the History of Science'' (1988): 1\u201331.\n*{{cite journal |author=Christie JR |title=Historiography of chemistry in the eighteenth century: Hermann Boerhaave and William Cullen |journal=Ambix |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages=4\u201319 |year=1994 |pmid=11616322 |doi=10.1179/amb.1994.41.1.4}}\n* Eddy, M. D. ''The Language of Mineralogy: John Walker, Chemistry and the Edinburgh Medical School, 1750\u20131800'' (Aldershot: 2008).\n* Eddy, M. D. \"The Aberdeen Agricola: Chemical Principles and Practice in James Aderson's Georgics and Geology\", in L. Principe (Ed.), ''New Narratives in Eighteenth-Century Chemistry'' (Dordrecht: Springer, 2007).\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== William Cullen and medicine ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Crellin JK |title=William Cullen: his calibre as a teacher, and an unpublished introduction to his A Treatise of the Materia Medica, London, 1773 |journal=Medical History |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=79\u201387 |date=January 1971 |pmid=4929623 |pmc=1034117 |doi=10.1017/s0025727300016148}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Johnstone RW |title=William Cullen |journal=Medical History |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201346 |date=January 1959 |pmid=13632206 |pmc=1034445 |doi=10.1017/s0025727300024236}}\n*{{cite journal |author=McGirr EM |title=William Cullen MD (1710\u20131790) |journal=Scottish Medical Journal |volume=36 |issue=1 |page=6 |date=February 1991 |pmid=2031172|doi=10.1177/003693309103600103 }}\n*{{cite journal |author=McGirr EM, Stoddart W |title=Changing theories in 18th-century medicine. The inheritance and legacy of William Cullen |journal=Scottish Medical Journal |volume=36 |issue=1 |pages=23\u20136 |date=February 1991 |pmid=2031170|doi=10.1177/003693309103600112 }}\n*{{cite journal |author=Risse GB |title='Doctor William Cullen, physician, Edinburgh': a consultation practice in the Eighteenth Century |journal=Bulletin of the History of Medicine |volume=48 |issue=3 |pages=338\u201351 |year=1974 |pmid=4618142}}\n*{{cite journal |author= |title=William Cullen (1710\u20131790) |journal=JAMA |volume=188 |issue= 4|pages=388\u20139 |date=April 1964 |pmid=14114029 |doi=10.1001/jama.1964.03060300050015}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Cramer M, De Morsier G |trans-title=Teachings of the physician William Cullen of Edinburg (1712\u20131790) transcribed by his student physician Louis Odier of Geneva (1748\u20131817) |language=French |journal=Gesnerus |volume=33 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=217\u201327 |year=1976 |pmid=793940 |title=Teachings of the physician William Cullen of Edinburg (1712\u20131790) transcribed by his student physician Louis Odier of Geneva (1748\u20131817)}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Dubois JC |trans-title=Neuroses and practical medicine in the works of William Cullen |language=French |journal=Annales M\u00e9dico-Psychologiques |volume=143 |issue=6 |pages=572\u20137 |date=June 1985 |pmid=3909876 |title=Neuroses and practical medicine in the works of William Cullen}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Risse GB |title=William Cullen and child care. A 1788 letter |journal=Clio Medica |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=65\u20137 |date=March 1973 |pmid=4129567}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Stott R |title=William Cullen and Edinburgh medicine: a reappraisal |journal=The Society for the Social History of Medicine Bulletin |volume=38 |issue= |pages=7\u20139 |date=June 1986 |pmid=11612030}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Stott R |title=Health and virtue: or, how to keep out of harm's way. Lectures on pathology and therapeutics by William Cullen c. 1770 |journal=Medical History |volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=123\u201342 |date=April 1987 |pmid=3550326 |pmc=1139708 |doi=10.1017/s0025727300046536}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.cullenproject.ac.uk/ The Consultation Letters of Dr William Cullen (1710\u20131790), University of Glasgow]\n*[http://www.gla.ac.uk/services/specialcollections/collectionsa-z/cullenpapers/ Papers of William Cullen at Special Collections, the University of Glasgow]\n*[https://archive.is/20121223065856/http://www.rcpe.ac.uk/library/find/manuscript/c.php Papers of William Cullen at the Royal College of Physicians, Edinburgh]\n*[http://www.chem.gla.ac.uk/~alanc/dept/cullen.htm Extracts from Senatus Minutes, University of Glasgow]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080607230109/http://www.chem.ed.ac.uk/public/professors/cullen.html Biography by W. P. Doyle] at University of Edinburgh, School of Chemistry\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120204201758/http://www.nahste.ac.uk/isaar/GB_0237_NAHSTE_P0251.html Biography, qualifications, sources] at Navigational Aids for the History of Science, Technology & the Environment\n*{{UK National Archives ID}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cullen, William}}\n[[Category:1710 births]]\n[[Category:1790 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Scottish chemists]]\n[[Category:18th-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:18th-century Scottish writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hamilton Academy]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:People from Hamilton, South Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish agronomists]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:History of mental health in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Members of the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Founder Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Scottish surgeons]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|William Cullen}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = William Cullen\n|image             = William Cullen.jpg\n|image_size        =\n|caption           = William Cullen\n|birth_date        = 15 April 1710\n|birth_place       = [[Hamilton, Scotland|Hamilton]], [[Lanarkshire]], [[Scotland]]<ref>Thomson, John. [https://books.google.com/books?id=F0EBAAAAQAAJ&dq=William%20Cullen%20John%20Thomson&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false ''An Account of the Life, Lectures and Writings of William Cullen, M.D. Volume 1'']. William Blackwood & T. Cadell, 1832, p. 1.</ref>\n|death_date        = {{d-da|5 February 1790|15 April 1710}}\n|death_place       = [[Edinburgh, Scotland|Edinburgh]], Scotland<ref>Thomson, John; Thomson, William; Craigie, David. [https://books.google.com/books?id=9SwAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA660#v=onepage&q&f=false ''An Account of the Life, Lectures and Writings of William Cullen, M.D. Volume 2'']. William Blackwood & Sons, 1859, p. 660.</ref>\n|residence         =\n|citizenship       =\n|nationality       = Scottish\n|alma_mater        = [[University of Glasgow]] <br /> [[University of Edinburgh]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|notable_students  = [[Joseph Black]], [[Benjamin Rush]], [[John Walker (natural historian)|John Walker]], [[John Morgan (physician)|John Morgan]], [[George Fordyce]], [[William Withering]], [[John Haygarth]], [[John Moore (Scottish physician)|John Moore]], [[John Brown (doctor)|John Brown]], [[Robert Willan]], [[Sir Gilbert Blane]], [[John Coakley Lettsom]]\n|known_for         = Teaching at the [[Edinburgh Medical School]], author of popular medical textbook ''First Lines of the Practice of Physic'', [[Scottish Enlightenment]] figure and mentor to [[Joseph Black]]\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        =\n|influenced        =\n|signature         =\n|footnotes         =\n|ethnicity         =\n|field             = Medicine, [[Chemistry]], Agriculture\n|work_institutions =\n|prizes            =\n|religion          =\n}}\n[[File:Cameo of William Cullen (close-up), Hunterian Museum, Glasgow.jpg|thumb|Cameo of William Cullen (close-up), Hunterian Museum, Glasgow]]\n[[File:Cullen William.jpg|thumb|William Cullen]]\n[[File:Burial enclosure of William and Robert Cullen - geograph.org.uk - 1050342.jpg|thumb|Burial enclosure of William and Robert Cullen in Kirknewton]]\n'''William Cullen''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] [[FRSE]] [[FRCPE]] [[FPSG]] ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u028c|l|\u0259n}}; 15 April 1710&nbsp;\u2013 5 February 1790) was a Scottish physician, chemist and agriculturalist, and one of the most important professors at the [[Edinburgh Medical School]], during its heyday as the leading centre of medical education in the English-speaking world.<ref>Thomson, John. [https://books.google.com/books?id=F0EBAAAAQAAJ&dq=William%20Cullen%20John%20Thomson&pg=PR3#v=onepage&q&f=false ''An Account of the Life, Lectures and Writings of William Cullen, M.D. Volume 1'']. William Blackwood & T. Cadell, 1832.</ref>\n\nCullen was also a central figure in the [[Scottish Enlightenment]]. He was [[David Hume]]'s physician and friend, and on intimate terms with [[Adam Smith]], [[Lord Kames]] (with whom he discussed theoretical and practical aspects of husbandry), [[Joseph Black]], [[John Millar (philosopher)|John Millar]], and [[Adam Ferguson]], among others.\n\nHe was President of the Royal College of Physicians and Surgeons of Glasgow (1746\u201347), President of the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]] (1773\u20131775) and First Physician to the King in Scotland (1773\u20131790).<ref>Doig, A., Ferguson, J. P. S., Milne, I. A., and Passmore, R. ''William Cullen and the Eighteenth Century Medical World''. Edinburgh University Press, 1993, pp. xii\u2013xiii.</ref> He was also, incidentally, one of the prime movers in obtaining a [[royal charter]] for the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh, resulting in the formation of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] in 1783.<ref name=\"Waterston\">{{cite book\n |last1       = Waterston\n |first1      = Charles D\n |last2       = Macmillan Shearer\n |first2      = A\n |title       = Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783\u20132002: Biographical Index\n |url         = http://www.rse.org.uk/fellowship/fells_indexp1.pdf\n |accessdate  = 29 September 2010\n |volume      = I\n |date        = July 2006\n |publisher   = [[The Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n |location    = Edinburgh\n |isbn        = 978-0-902198-84-5\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061004113545/http://www.rse.org.uk/fellowship/fells_indexp1.pdf\n |archivedate = 4 October 2006\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nCullen was a beloved teacher, and many of his students became influential figures in their own right. His best-known students\u2014many of whom continued to correspond with him during his long life\u2014included (in addition to [[Joseph Black]], who became his colleague) [[Benjamin Rush]], a central figure in the founding of the United States of America; [[John Morgan (physician)|John Morgan]], who founded the first medical school in the American colonies (the Medical School at the [[College of Philadelphia]]);<ref>{{Cite journal|jstor = 3143563|title = Some American Students of \"That Shining Oracle of Physic,\" Dr. William Cullen of Edinburgh, 1755-1766|journal = Proceedings of the American Philosophical Society|volume = 94|issue = 3|pages = 275\u2013281|last1 = Bell|first1 = Whitfield J|year = 1950}}</ref> [[William Withering]], the discoverer of [[digitalis]]; [[Sir Gilbert Blane]], medical reformer of the [[Royal Navy]]; and [[John Coakley Lettsom]], the philanthropist and founder of the [[Medical Society of London]].<ref>Doig, A., Ferguson, J. P. S., Milne, I. A., and Passmore, R. ''William Cullen and the Eighteenth Century Medical World''. Edinburgh University Press, 1993, esp. pp. 40\u201355.</ref>\n\nSpecial mention must be made of Cullen's student-turned-opponent, [[John Brown (doctor)|John Brown]], who developed the medical system known as [[Brunonian system of medicine|Brunonianism]], which rivalled Cullen's. This was to have immense influence, especially in Italy and Germany, during the end of the eighteenth and beginning of the nineteenth century.<ref>Bynum, W.F. and Porter, Roy. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/issues/172551/ ''Brunonianism in Britain and Europe'']. ''Medical History'', Supplement No. 8 (1988), pp. ix\u2013x.</ref>\n\nCullen was also a successful author. He published a number of medical textbooks, mostly for the use of his students, though they were popular throughout Europe and the American colonies as well. His best known work was ''First Lines of the Practice of Physic'', which was published in a series of editions between 1777 and 1784.<ref>Doig, A., Ferguson, J. P. S., Milne, I. A., and Passmore, R. ''William Cullen and the Eighteenth Century Medical World''. Edinburgh University Press, 1993, esp. pp. 34\u201339.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCullen was born in [[Hamilton, Scotland|Hamilton]], Lanarkshire.<ref name=\"royalsoced.org.uk\">https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp1.pdf</ref> His father William was a lawyer retained by the [[Duke of Hamilton]] as [[Factor (Scotland)|factor]], and his mother was Elizabeth Roberton of Whistlebury.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nahste.ac.uk/isaar/GB_0237_NAHSTE_P0251.html |title=Cullen &#124; William &#124; 1710\u20131790 &#124; physician, chemist and metallurgist |publisher=Nahste.ac.uk |accessdate=20 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204201758/http://www.nahste.ac.uk/isaar/GB_0237_NAHSTE_P0251.html |archivedate=4 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.familysearch.org/eng/search/frameset_search.asp |title=Free Family History and Genealogy Records \u2013 |publisher=Familysearch.org |date= |accessdate=22 April 2013}}</ref> He studied at the Old Grammar School of Hamilton (renamed in 1848 The [[Hamilton Academy]]), then, in 1726, began a General Studies arts course at the [[University of Glasgow]]. He began his medical training as apprentice to John Paisley, a [[Glasgow]] apothecary surgeon, then spent 1729 as surgeon on a merchant vessel trading between London and the [[West Indies]]. After two years as assistant apothecary to Mr Murray of Henrietta Street, London, he returned to Scotland in 1732 to establish himself in general medical practice in the parish of [[Shotts]], Lanarkshire. From 1734 to 1736 he studied medicine at the [[University of Edinburgh]], where he became interested in chemistry, and was one of the founders of the [[Royal Medical Society]] in his first year of study.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cullenproject.ac.uk/about/|title=About the Cullen Project|last=|first=|date=|website=The Cullen Project|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1736 he began medical practice in Hamilton, where he rapidly acquired a high reputation. He also continued his study of the [[natural science]]s, especially of [[chemistry]]. From 1737 to 1740 [[William Hunter (anatomist)|William Hunter]] was his resident pupil, and at one time they proposed to enter into partnership. In 1740 Cullen was awarded the degree of MD from [[Glasgow University]]. In 1741, he married and started his family. He became ordinary medical attendant to James Douglas, 5th [[Duke of Hamilton]] (1703\u201343), his family, and his livestock. In 1744, following the Duke's death, the Cullens moved to [[Glasgow]].\n\nIn Glasgow he gave extramural lectures for the University, on physiology, botany, materia medica, and chemistry. His great abilities, enthusiasm, and use of practical demonstrations for instruction, made him a successful and highly popular teacher, attracting large classes. At the same time he also maintained a medical practice. In 1747, Cullen was awarded Britain's first independent lectureship in Chemistry and was elected President of the Faculty of Physicians and Surgeons of Glasgow. In 1748 while in Glasgow, Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although is not credited with a usable application. In 1751 he was appointed [[Regius Professor of Medicine and Therapeutics, Glasgow|Professor of the Practice of Medicine]], although he continued to lecture on chemistry.\n\n==Edinburgh==\nIn 1755 he was enticed by [[Lord Kames]] to become Professor of Chemistry and Medicine at the [[University of Edinburgh]]. It was in Edinburgh, in 1756, that he gave the first documented public demonstration of artificial [[refrigeration]].<ref>William Cullen, ''Of the Cold Produced by Evaporating Fluids and of Some Other Means of Producing Cold,'' '''in''' Essays and Observations Physical and Literary Read Before a Society in Edinburgh and Published by Them, II, (Edinburgh 1756)</ref> Cullen used a pump to create a partial [[vacuum]] over a container of [[diethyl ether]], which then [[boiling point|boiled]], absorbing [[Heat of vaporization|heat]] from the surroundings. This created a small amount of ice, but the process found no commercial application.\n\nFrom 1757 he delivered lectures on [[clinical medicine]] in the [[Edinburgh Royal Infirmary]]. On the death of [[Charles Alston (professor)|Charles Alston]] in 1760, Cullen at the request of the students undertook to finish his course of lectures on ''materia medica''; he delivered an entirely new course, notes of which were published in an unauthorised edition in 1771, but which he re-wrote and issued as ''A Treatise on Materia Medica'' in 1789.\n\nOn the death of [[Robert Whytt]], the professor of the institutes of medicine, Cullen accepted the chair, at the same time resigning that of chemistry. In the same year he had been an unsuccessful candidate for the professorship of the practice of physic (medicine), but subsequently an arrangement was made between him and [[John Gregory (moralist)|John Gregory]], the successful candidate, by which they both agreed to deliver alternate courses on the theory and practice of medicine. This arrangement continued until the sudden death of Gregory in 1773. Cullen was then appointed sole professor of the practice of physic, and he continued in this office until a few months before his death.\n\nIn 1783 Cullen (together with his sons) was a co-founder of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]].<ref name=\"royalsoced.org.uk\"/>\n\nHe died on 5 February 1790 at his home Ormiston Hill<ref>Williamson's Street Directory 1784</ref> in [[Kirknewton, West Lothian]], and is buried in the churchyard there. His son [[Robert Cullen, Lord Cullen|Robert]] lies with him.\n\n==Influence==\n\nCullen taught many students who would go on to influential careers in British science.  Indeed, a large number of the doctors who taught in Edinburgh's medical school from the 1790s to 1810s had studied with him, including the chemist Joseph Black, the anatomist Alexander Monro Secundus, and the naturalist [[John Walker (natural historian)|John Walker]]. Cullen's emphasis on the practical benefits of chemistry made his ideas popular amongst farmers, industrialists, naturalists and doctors alike.  His influence on these fields was felt though the writings of his students, particularly in the books of John Anderson, the 'Aberdeen Agricola',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Eddy|first1=Matthew Daniel|title='The Aberdeen Agricola: Chemical Principles and Practice in James Anderson's Georgics and Geology |journal=In Lawrence Principe (Ed.), New Narratives in Eighteenth-Century Chemistry|volume=18|date=Springer: 2007|pages=139\u2013156|url=https://www.academia.edu/3667295|doi=10.1007/978-1-4020-6278-0_7|isbn=978-1-4020-6273-5|series=Archimedes}}</ref> and the lectures given by Joseph Black and John Walker from the 1770s to 1790s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Eddy|first1=Matthew Daniel|title=The Language of Mineralogy: John Walker, Chemistry and the Edinburgh Medical School 1750\u20131800|date=2008|publisher=Ashgate|url=https://www.academia.edu/1112014}}</ref>\n\nBy studying the symptoms of diseases, Cullen classified diseases into different classes. One class of diseases was called \"neuroses.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Science and the Practice of Medicine in the Nineteenth Century|last=Bynum|first=William|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1994|isbn=978-0-521-27205-6|location=Cambridge|pages=15\u201316|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Medical practice ==\nIn the 18th century, there were three primary professions in medicine: physicians, surgeons, and apothecaries, although the barriers among them were starting to become blurred. William Cullen practiced as all three.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=William Cullen and the eighteenth century medical world : a bicentenary exhibition and symposium arranged by the Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh in 1990|last=Milne|first=I.|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|year=1993|isbn=978-0-7486-0302-2|location=Edinburgh|pages=110\u2013160}}</ref> Because medical practitioners were not as established as they are now, patients generally took advice from a myriad of sources, including personal experience, books, and several consultations. Furthermore, because the diagnostic tools were not as advanced, patient history was the primary and most important information for the physicians to diagnose their patients.<ref name=\":0\" /> There were no strict government regulations in place for physicians, surgeons, and apothecaries.<ref name=\":0\" /> As a result, to become successful in the medical marketplace depended more on social skills than on medical expertise, similar to other forms of businesses.<ref name=\":0\" /> Cullen was one of the more successful physicians because of his shrewdness in handling difficult patients.<ref name=\":0\" /> Teaching at the University and seeing patients at the Edinburgh Infirmary as charity also helped Cullen become more famous.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMany of Cullen's consultations were done through written letters sent by patients from Scottish cities and towns.<ref name=\":0\" /> Cullen managed his consultations with great efficiency; he usually read the letters early in the morning and his secretary-amanuensis would record and mail back his responses.<ref name=\":0\" /> He then went around Edinburgh to visit patients. This form of epistolary consultations was often limited by the literacy and socioeconomic status of the patients. Patients who would write letters to Cullen were usually in the upper and middle class. Besides letters from patients, he also consulted physicians, often students he had taught.<ref name=\":0\" /> Based on how his letters were written, Cullen was most likely a \"tactful and compassionate practitioner.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Like many physicians in his time, Cullen would often prescribe therapeutics \"to support the patient's endangered constitution and assist the body's natural healing tendencies.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> This is because medical practitioners at the time mostly believed that diseases and illnesses were unique to different patients depending on their constitutions.\n\n== Medical teaching ==\nAccording to Rocca, Cullen was known for systemizing and promoting medical knowledge rather than producing original research.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Brain, Mind and Medicine: Essays in Eighteenth-Century Neuroscience - Springer|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-0-387-70967-3|year = 2007|isbn = 978-0-387-70966-6|last1 = Whitaker|first1 = Harry|last2=Smith|first2=C.U.M|last3=Finger|first3=Stanley}}</ref> Despite the lack of original work, some believed that Cullen's attempt to organize existing knowledge was actually a sign of his \"practical sagacity\" as a practitioner.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|title=William Cullen and the eighteenth century medical world : a bicentenary exhibition and symposium arranged by the Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh in 1990|last=Milne|first=I.|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|year=1993|isbn=978-0-7486-0302-2|location=Edinburgh|pages=110\u2013160}}</ref> He was a lecturer for more than forty years.<ref name=\":02\" /> In order to understand Cullen's medical teaching at the time, it is important to understand Cullen's conception of \"system\" as he taught it in his classes. Cullen described a system as \"an organised body of opinions on particular topics in the medical curriculum.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> He also referred to system as the principles in his book ''First Lines of the Practice of Physic.''<ref name=\":02\" /> There were many possible reasons behind Cullen's emphasis of the system of medicine. In the 18th century, a period of Scottish Enlightenment, there were competing theories about the mechanisms of the human body and the causes of diseases proposed by different professors, who competed for students' teaching fees.<ref name=\":02\" /> Thus, having an underlying system of medical knowledge was a practical way to organize the knowledge coherently for the students.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nLike many prominent medical figures in the 18th century, William Cullen took a great interest in the nervous system. He defined the nervous system as an \"animated machine\" whose main function is to \"perform a variety of motions,\" communicate and interact with \"external bodies.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Cullen believed that the nervous system was composed of four elements: the medullary substance, consisting of the brain and the spinal cord, the membranous nerves, the sensory nerves, and the muscular fibers.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nCullen's understanding of the nervous system was also influenced by his contemporaries, one of whom was [[Albrecht von Haller]] (1708\u20131777).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eds.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?sid=fe84e265-d9e0-4c7c-a22d-8983fc63ab0a@sessionmgr4010&vid=0&hid=4213&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZSZzY29wZT1zaXRl#AN=101560475&db=hia|title=Cullen, a Cautionary Tale: EBSCOhost|website=eds.a.ebscohost.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref> Haller proposed that tissues, including muscles, were characterized by \"irritability\" (or contractility), while nerves were characterized by \"sensibility\" (or feeling).<ref name=\":1\" /> Using Haller's characterization, Cullen defined disease \"as an excess or deficiency of sensibility.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> However, Cullen interpreted sensibility as \"muscle mobility and vigour\" and diseases were caused by the imbalance of irritability and sensibility.<ref name=\":1\" /> Based on this definition of disease, his therapeutics \"either stimulated or sedated the nervous system.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> He categorized diseases into four main classes: pyrexiae, neuroses, cachexiae, and locales. Within the classes were nineteen orders and 132 genera.<ref name=\":1\" /> The four orders of neuroses were comata, adynamiae, spasmi and vesaniae.<ref name=\":1\" /> Comata was defined as \"a diminution of voluntary motion, with sleep, or a deprivation of the senses.\" Adynamiae is defined as \"a diminution of the involuntary motions, whether vital or natural.\" Spasmi was defined as \"irregular motions of the muscles or muscular fibers.\" Vesaniae was defined as \"disorders of the judgement without any pyrexia or coma.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nCullen's emphasis on the importance of the nervous system was driven by the understanding that the nervous system controls the human body and therefore, \"all diseases may, in some sense, be called affections of the nervous system, because, in almost every disease, the nerves are more or less hurt.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Although Cullen's nosology did not last very long, Cullen's influential teachings on medical knowledge and his attempt to systematize and generalize medical knowledge were integral parts of 18th century Scottish Enlightenment.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Family==\n\nIn 1741 he married Anne (or Anna) Johnstone (d.1786).\n\nHe was father to the judge [[Robert Cullen, Lord Cullen]] and to the physician [[Henry Cullen]]. Cullen's eldest son Robert became a Scottish judge in 1796 under the title of Lord Cullen later Baron Cullen,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/portrait.asp?search=as&grp=1095%3BScottish+sitters+and+artists&lDate=&LinkID=mp55787&rNo=0&role=sit |title=NPG D2239; Robert Cullen, Baron Cullen |publisher=Npg.org.uk |date= |accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref> and was known for his powers of [[impressionist (entertainment)|mimicry]].\n\n==Publications==\nBecause of the wide popularity of Cullen's work, many of his publications were translated into a multitude of languages across Europe.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Science and the Practice of Medicine in the Nineteenth Century|last=Bynum|first=W.F.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1994|isbn=978-0-521-27205-6|location=New York|pages=11|quote=|via=}}</ref> Cullen's most popular and successful work was his medical textbook ''First Lines of the Practice of Physic'', published in two volumes in 1777 and expanded with each edition until it reached four volumes in its final edition (1784).\n\nHis first book-length publication was ''Synopsis Nosologiae Methodicae'' (1769), Cullen's very influential nosology, or classification of diseases. His next publication was also a medical textbook, and it dealt with the Institutions of medicine, i.e. medical theory. Its full title was ''Institutions of Medicine. Part I. Physiology'' (1772) because it focused on physiology, which was traditionally only one part of the Institutions (pathology and therapeutics were also essential parts of medical theory). It went through two more editions (1777 & 1785).\n\nWork on his magnum opus, ''First Lines of Practice of Physic'', occupied much of his time in the 1770s and 1780s, but he did manage one final publication. This was his two volume ''A Treatise of the Materia Medica'' (1789), which was highly valued by other medical practitioners throughout Europe.\n\nThus, the following works, with their dates of publication (including multiple editions), comprise the majority of Cullen's ''oevre'':\n\n*''Synopsis Nosologiae Methodicae'' (1769; 1771; 1780; 1785)\n* ''Lectures on the Materia medica''. 2nd Ed. Dublin : Whitestone, 1781. [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:061:2-169327 Digital edition] of the [[University and State Library D\u00fcsseldorf]].\n* ''Cours de Mati\u00e8re m\u00e9dicale.'' Paris, 1788. [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:061:2-148946 Digital edition] of the [[University and State Library D\u00fcsseldorf]].\n*''Institutions of Medicine. Part I. Physiology'' (1772; 1777; 1785)\n*''First Lines of the Practice of Physic'' (1777; 1778; 1781; 1784; 1793 ([http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t1zc7sg8v vol.&nbsp;1]; [http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t4hm53f54?urlappend=%3Bseq=5 vol.&nbsp;2]))\n*''A Treatise of the Materia Medica'' (1789)\n** ''Trait\u00e9 de Mati\u00e8re m\u00e9dicale'' translated by \u00c9douard Fran\u00e7ois Marie Bosquillon. Published: vol. 1 \u2013 3. Pavie : Sauveur, 1791. [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:061:2-148969 Digital edition] of the [[University and State Library D\u00fcsseldorf]].\n** ''Trattato di Materia medica''. Involved: Dalladecima, Angelo. 2. Ed. Erschienen: Bd. 1 \u2013 6. Padova : Bettinelli, 1798. [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:061:2-148955 Digital edition] of the [[University and State Library D\u00fcsseldorf]].\n\nCullen also published a few, shorter works (e.g. \"A Letter to Lord Cathcart\" in 1776), which have not been included in this list.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Cullen, William|volume=7|pages=616\u2013617}}\n\n=== Basic biographical sources ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Thomson, John. [https://books.google.com/books?id=F0EBAAAAQAAJ&dq=William%20Cullen%20John%20Thomson&pg=PR3#v=onepage&q&f=false ''An Account of the Life, Lectures and Writings of William Cullen, M.D. Volume 1'']. William Blackwood & T. Cadell, 1832.\n*Thomson, John; Thomson, William; [[David Craigie|Craigie, David]]. [https://books.google.com/books?id=9SwAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR1 ''An Account of the Life, Lectures and Writings of William Cullen, M.D. Volume 2'']. William Blackwood & Sons, 1859. This book, in conjunction with its predecessor (see previous reference), is the standard biography of William Cullen's life and thought.\n*Doig, A., Ferguson, J. P. S., Milne, I. A., and Passmore, R (Editors). ''William Cullen and the Eighteenth Century Medical World''. Edinburgh University Press, 1993. This collection of edited essays is the most recent, full-length work on the life and thought of William Cullen. It was the result of an exhibition and symposium at the Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh in 1990 to commemorate the bicentenary of Cullen's death.\n*Bynum, W. F.. \"William Cullen (1710\u20131790).\" ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''. Oxford University Press, 2004. http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/6874.\n* Eddy, M. D. 'Dr. William Cullen, M.D., (1710\u20131790)', ''New Dictionary of Scientific Biography'', Noretta Koertge (ed.), (New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 2007).\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== William Cullen and chemistry ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Donovan, Arthur L. ''Philosophical Chemistry in the Scottish Enlightenment: The Doctrines and Discoveries of William Cullen and Joseph Black''. Edinburgh: University Press, 1975.\n*J V Golinski, \"Utility and Audience in Eighteenth-Century Chemistry: Case Studies of William Cullen and Joseph Priestley,\" ''The British Journal for the History of Science'' (1988): 1\u201331.\n*{{cite journal |author=Christie JR |title=Historiography of chemistry in the eighteenth century: Hermann Boerhaave and William Cullen |journal=Ambix |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages=4\u201319 |year=1994 |pmid=11616322 |doi=10.1179/amb.1994.41.1.4}}\n* Eddy, M. D. ''The Language of Mineralogy: John Walker, Chemistry and the Edinburgh Medical School, 1750\u20131800'' (Aldershot: 2008).\n* Eddy, M. D. \"The Aberdeen Agricola: Chemical Principles and Practice in James Aderson's Georgics and Geology\", in L. Principe (Ed.), ''New Narratives in Eighteenth-Century Chemistry'' (Dordrecht: Springer, 2007).\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== William Cullen and medicine ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Crellin JK |title=William Cullen: his calibre as a teacher, and an unpublished introduction to his A Treatise of the Materia Medica, London, 1773 |journal=Medical History |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=79\u201387 |date=January 1971 |pmid=4929623 |pmc=1034117 |doi=10.1017/s0025727300016148}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Johnstone RW |title=William Cullen |journal=Medical History |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201346 |date=January 1959 |pmid=13632206 |pmc=1034445 |doi=10.1017/s0025727300024236}}\n*{{cite journal |author=McGirr EM |title=William Cullen MD (1710\u20131790) |journal=Scottish Medical Journal |volume=36 |issue=1 |page=6 |date=February 1991 |pmid=2031172|doi=10.1177/003693309103600103 }}\n*{{cite journal |author=McGirr EM, Stoddart W |title=Changing theories in 18th-century medicine. The inheritance and legacy of William Cullen |journal=Scottish Medical Journal |volume=36 |issue=1 |pages=23\u20136 |date=February 1991 |pmid=2031170|doi=10.1177/003693309103600112 }}\n*{{cite journal |author=Risse GB |title='Doctor William Cullen, physician, Edinburgh': a consultation practice in the Eighteenth Century |journal=Bulletin of the History of Medicine |volume=48 |issue=3 |pages=338\u201351 |year=1974 |pmid=4618142}}\n*{{cite journal |author= |title=William Cullen (1710\u20131790) |journal=JAMA |volume=188 |issue= 4|pages=388\u20139 |date=April 1964 |pmid=14114029 |doi=10.1001/jama.1964.03060300050015}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Cramer M, De Morsier G |trans-title=Teachings of the physician William Cullen of Edinburg (1712\u20131790) transcribed by his student physician Louis Odier of Geneva (1748\u20131817) |language=French |journal=Gesnerus |volume=33 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=217\u201327 |year=1976 |pmid=793940 |title=Teachings of the physician William Cullen of Edinburg (1712\u20131790) transcribed by his student physician Louis Odier of Geneva (1748\u20131817)}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Dubois JC |trans-title=Neuroses and practical medicine in the works of William Cullen |language=French |journal=Annales M\u00e9dico-Psychologiques |volume=143 |issue=6 |pages=572\u20137 |date=June 1985 |pmid=3909876 |title=Neuroses and practical medicine in the works of William Cullen}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Risse GB |title=William Cullen and child care. A 1788 letter |journal=Clio Medica |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=65\u20137 |date=March 1973 |pmid=4129567}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Stott R |title=William Cullen and Edinburgh medicine: a reappraisal |journal=The Society for the Social History of Medicine Bulletin |volume=38 |issue= |pages=7\u20139 |date=June 1986 |pmid=11612030}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Stott R |title=Health and virtue: or, how to keep out of harm's way. Lectures on pathology and therapeutics by William Cullen c. 1770 |journal=Medical History |volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=123\u201342 |date=April 1987 |pmid=3550326 |pmc=1139708 |doi=10.1017/s0025727300046536}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.cullenproject.ac.uk/ The Consultation Letters of Dr William Cullen (1710\u20131790), University of Glasgow]\n*[http://www.gla.ac.uk/services/specialcollections/collectionsa-z/cullenpapers/ Papers of William Cullen at Special Collections, the University of Glasgow]\n*[https://archive.is/20121223065856/http://www.rcpe.ac.uk/library/find/manuscript/c.php Papers of William Cullen at the Royal College of Physicians, Edinburgh]\n*[http://www.chem.gla.ac.uk/~alanc/dept/cullen.htm Extracts from Senatus Minutes, University of Glasgow]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080607230109/http://www.chem.ed.ac.uk/public/professors/cullen.html Biography by W. P. Doyle] at University of Edinburgh, School of Chemistry\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120204201758/http://www.nahste.ac.uk/isaar/GB_0237_NAHSTE_P0251.html Biography, qualifications, sources] at Navigational Aids for the History of Science, Technology & the Environment\n*{{UK National Archives ID}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cullen, William}}\n[[Category:1710 births]]\n[[Category:1790 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Scottish chemists]]\n[[Category:18th-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:18th-century Scottish writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hamilton Academy]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:People from Hamilton, South Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish agronomists]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:History of mental health i