{"title_page": "Marta Xargay", "text_new": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Marta Xargay\n| image = \n| number = 10\n| position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lbs = 157\n| league = [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|LF]]\n| team = [[Uni Girona CB]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|12|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Girona]], Spain\n| nationality = Spanish\n| career_start = 2009\n| career_end = \n| highlights = *[[EuroLeague Women|EuroLeague]] Champion (2011)\n*2x [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|Spanish League]] champion (2011, 2013)\n*3x [[Copa de la Reina de Baloncesto|Spanish Cup]] champion (2012, 1014, 2015)\n*3x [[Czech Women's Basketball League|Czech League]] champion (2016, 2017, 2018)\n| years1 = 1996\u20132003\n| team1 = C.E. Vedruna\n| years2 = 2003\u20132005\n| team2 = C.E.S.E.T.\n| years3 = 2005\u20132009\n| team3 = [[Uni Girona CB]]\n| years4 = 2009\u20132015\n| team4 = [[CB Avenida]]\n| years5 = 2015\u20132016\n| team5 = [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| years6 = 2015\u20132018\n| team6 = [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|USK Praha]]\n| years7 = 2018\u20132019\n| team7 = [[Dynamo Kursk]]\n| years8 = 2020-\n| team8 = [[Uni Girona CB]]\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{bkw|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 FIBA World Championship for Women|2014 Turkey]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2018 FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|2018 Spain]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket Women|EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket Women 2013|2013 France]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket Women 2017|2017 Czech Republic]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIBA Women's EuroBasket 2019|2019 Serbia/Latvia]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[EuroBasket Women 2015|2015 Hungary/Romania]]|}}\n}}\n'''Marta Xargay Casademont''' (born 20 December 1990) is a Spanish professional [[basketball]] player. She played for [[Phoenix Mercury]] of the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]], and currently for the Spanish team [[Uni Girona CB]] and the [[Spain women's national basketball team]]. She has represented national team since [[EuroBasket Women 2011]] competition.<ref>[http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_KNce8jInH7Qj1EsyH5rjn2.compID_jr6ZiXqeGhMBtfq1yxqV83.roundID_7843.season_2011.teamID_96446.playerID_57672.html FIBA Europe profile]</ref> She won [[EuroLeague Women 2010\u201311]] with Perfumer\u00edas Avenida Baloncesto. She left Spain in 2015, joining both USK Praha of the [[Czech Women's Basketball League|Czech League]] in 2015 and the Phoenix Mercury of the [[WNBA]] on 11 February 2015.<ref>[http://www.wnba.com/mercury/news/xargay_150211.html Mercury Sign Guard Marta Xargay] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214031638/http://www.wnba.com/mercury/news/xargay_150211.html |date=14 February 2015 }}</ref> In September 2018 she signed for [[Dynamo Kursk]] of the [[Russian Women's Basketball Premier League|Russian Premier League]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/baloncesto/mundial-femenino/2018/09/14/5b9ba2fee2704e42a08b45e7.html Marca.com (in Spanish)]</ref>, and in January 2020 she returned to his youth club [[Uni Girona CB]].\n\n==Club career==\nXargay started playing basketball from a young age in clubs in her hometown [[Girona]], entering the youth levels of [[Uni Girona CB]] at 14 and making it to the senior team and the Spanish [[Liga Femenina 2 de Baloncesto|second tier]]. In 2009 she signed for [[CB Avenida]] from [[Salamanca]], where in the following six seasons she won two [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|leagues]], three [[Copa de la Reina de Baloncesto|cups]] and one [[2010\u201311 EuroLeague Women|EuroLeague]].\n\nDuring 2015 and 2016 she played both in the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wnba.com/player/marta-xargay-casademont/|title=Marta Xargay Casademont \u2013 WNBA.com \u2013 Official Site of the WNBA|work=WNBA.com \u2013 Official Site of the WNBA|access-date=3 October 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> with [[Phoenix Mercury]] and the European season with [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|USK Praha]], where she won the 2016, 2017 and 2018 [[Czech Women's Basketball League|Czech League]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eurobasket.com/Czech-Republic/basketball-League-ZBL_2016-2017.asp?women=1|title=ZBL_2016-2017 Basketball League CZECH-REPUBLIC \u2013 eurobasket|work=www.eurobasket.com|access-date=3 October 2017}}</ref> Due to her commitment to the [[Spain women's national basketball team|Spain national team]], she opted not to play in the WNBA in 2017 or 2018. She played for one and a half seasons in [[Russia]]n team [[Dynamo Kursk]], before returning to [[Uni Girona CB]] in January 2020. <ref>https://www.diaridegirona.cat/esports/2020/01/07/marta-xargay-torna-girona-quedar/1022485.html</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===WNBA===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Season\n!Team\n!GP\n!MPP\n!PPP\n!RPP\n!APP\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Phoenix Mercury]]\n|20\n|17.5\n|3.9\n|1.8\n|2.4\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Phoenix Mercury]]\n|15\n|19.8\n|5.7\n|1.7\n|2.7\n|}\n\n===EuroLeague and EuroCup statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\n|[[EuroLeague Women|EuroLeague winner]]\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Season\n!Team\n!GP\n!MPP\n!PPP\n!RPP\n!APP\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 EuroLeague Women|2009\u201310 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Halc\u00f3n Avenida]]\n|13\n|10.5\n|2.0\n|1.0\n|1.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;background:#afe6ba;\"|[[2010\u201311 EuroLeague Women|2010\u201311 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Halc\u00f3n Avenida]]\n|17\n|13.7\n|3.5\n|1.3\n|0.9\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 EuroLeague Women|2011\u201312 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|14\n|25.1\n|6.0\n|3.0\n|2.7\n|-\n||[[2012\u201313 EuroLeague Women|2012\u201313 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|14\n|26.1\n|7.9\n|3.1\n|2.9\n|-\n||[[2013\u201314 EuroLeague Women|2013\u201314 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|13\n|30.9\n|8.5\n|4.2\n|4.7\n|-\n||[[2014\u201315 EuroLeague Women|2014\u201315 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|16\n|28.1\n|8.1\n|3.6\n|3.3\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 EuroLeague Women|2015\u201316 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|CZE}} [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|ZVVZ USK Praha]]\n|17\n|19.7\n|4.9\n|2.1\n|2.0\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 EuroLeague Women|2016\u201317 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|CZE}} [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|ZVVZ USK Praha]]\n|19\n|30.8\n|11.0\n|3.3\n|3.4\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 EuroLeague Women|2017\u201318 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|CZE}} [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|ZVVZ USK Praha]]\n|15\n|36.0\n|11.6\n|4.0\n|6.6\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 EuroLeague Women|2018\u201319 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Dynamo Kursk]]\n|17\n|20.9\n|5.1\n|1.9\n|3.1\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 EuroLeague Women|2019\u201320 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Dynamo Kursk]]\n|8\n|24.6\n|4.0\n|2.9\n|2.5\n|-\n|\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Uni Girona CB|Spar CityLift Girona]]\n|6\n|21.4\n|7.3\n|2.7\n|2.7\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 EuroCup Women|2019\u201320 EuroCup]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Uni Girona CB|Spar CityLift Girona]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==National team==\nXargay started playing with [[Spain women's national basketball team|Spain]]'s youth teams at 16, winning a total of five medals from 2006 to 2010. She made her debut with the senior team in 2011. Up to 2017, she had 107 caps and 8 PPG,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://seleccionfemenina.feb.es/|title=Selecci\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola Absoluta Femenina de Baloncesto|website=seleccionfemenina.feb.es|access-date=3 October 2017}}</ref> participating in the [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Rio 2016]] Olympics, one [[FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|World Championships]] and four [[EuroBasket Women|European Championships]]:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/q/Marta%20XARGAY/pid/57672/_//players.html|title=archive.fiba.com: Players|website=archive.fiba.com|access-date=3 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n* [[File:Gold medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2006 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship for Women|2006 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2007 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship for Women|2007 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* 5th [[2008 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship for Women|2008 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2009 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship for Women|2009 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship for Women|2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship]] (''youth'') ('''''MVP''''')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2010 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship for Women|2010 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* 9th [[EuroBasket Women 2011|2011 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2013|2013 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Silver medal world centered-2.svg|16x16px]] [[2014 FIBA World Championship for Women|2014 World Championship]]\n* [[File:Bronze medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2015|2015 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Silver medal olympic.svg|16x16px]] [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2016 Summer Olympics]]\n* [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2017|2017 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Bronze medal world centered-2.svg|16x16px]] [[2018 FIBA World Championship for Women|2018 World Championship]]\n* [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2019|2019 Eurobasket]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_KNce8jInH7Qj1EsyH5rjn2.compID_jr6ZiXqeGhMBtfq1yxqV83.roundID_7843.season_2011.team